column14:

Once you wear these things a few times they feel as if they are a part of your foot. I even have my mother wearing these things now...go figure.

column6: Dr. Martens Unisex Wonder Balsam Shoe Polish
column14:
Use on all of my boots (see photo). I use Huberd's shoe grease for deep conditioning 1x/month. I use wonder balsam weekly on my workboots (I work in a foundry).

The photograph shows (l-r) Rocky Stockman Lacer (false tongue removed), Chippewa #20067, and LeHigh metguard (my workboots).

Boots were brushed with a horsehair brush, cleaned with water and Fiebing's saddlesoap, and buffed with wonder balsam.

I highly recommend the balsam. As you can see, it brightens the colour nicely, helps to waterproof the boot and leaves the leather feeling very healthy. It also, as you can see, slightly darkens the leather (however, my boots were already conditioned, so the leather on the lighter boots was even lighter prior to the photograph). However, the sheen and vivid finish on the leather really sets this stuff apart from other polishes. Highly recommend.

Note: Do not apply in thick, gloppy layers. Allow full penetration of the grain before a final brush and wear. Test on a small area prior to using on a full surface. I use my fingers, but make sure your sponge is clean and you have cleaned the leather prior to oiling.

column14:
I started running more regularly at the beginning of the year. I purchased these because I wanted to start running on the various trails around town. I already had the non-trail version of these shoes, so I was confident ordering the same size. The fit was the same, and the shoes were comfortable and seemed sturdy. I liked the colors too. The mesh on the shoes is pretty thin but it keeps them comfortable in the Texas heat. However, itâ€™s so thin that I can sometimes see the color of my socks through the shoe, which I think is a little odd.

I wore these shoes in a 5k race when it had been raining all day previous. The grips on the bottom of the shoes made my feet feel secure running on the wet and muddy ground, and I always wear these when the weather isnâ€™t great or when Iâ€™m going to be walking/jogging on unstable ground. Iâ€™ve had no trouble with blisters, and the shoes were comfortable right out of the box - no break in time needed. I find that some sneakers have extra long laces that get in the way, but the length on these were just right. When these wear out I will be happy to buy more Sauconys!

column13: Inexpensive sunglasses that block the glaring sun.
column14: These sunglasses are unisex. My son bought a pair and so did I. They're a bit wide for my small head but they fit him perfectly. The frames are hard plastic, not rubberized, which I prefer but they are comfortable. The lenses look as pictured and were not scratched at all when they arrived. They don't feel or look like super high priced sunglasses but they block out harsh sunlight and they don't distort things like some sunglasses do. I'm not sure how well they are made but they're $10.00 sunglasses. If I get a summer's wear out of them, that's fine with me. I have lots of pairs of sunglasses and like to mix up which I wear depending on my outfit and mood. These are great for sunny, casual days. I wear mine when walking the dog or in the car when the sun is glaring. They do the job and look pretty nice on. As I said, I didn't expect these to be super high quality or to look like a designer brand. They look fine though and so far, have held up well to not so gentle use. They're worth what I paid for them but I wouldn't pay much more. I really do prefer rubberized arms and polarized lenses. Recommended if you just want a pair of mirrored lens sunglasses to kick around in that aren't super high quality but DO block the sun.

column6: Tifosi Dolomite 2.0 Wrap Sunglasses
column13: Dolomite Is It's Name and Effing Up The Elements Is Its Game
column14: I wore these on a double century yesterday and they are quality glasses. Even on very steep, long descents I didn't find the wind issue to be a serious problem as others have stated. Yes, a bit of air does get in there but not enough to dry out my eyes. No issues for fogging up and performed well in the light rain I got near the top of Mt. Tamalpais. They stay on the nose comfortably and don't slip down, an issue I was having with my old pair of riding glasses. They also look cool. My problem with them is that I'm used to riding glasses that have larger frames. With these I was constantly aware that there are frames on the periphery that block lateral viewing to some extent. Will probably switch to darker lenses and use these as casual sunglasses because of that issue.

column6: Besgoods Polarized Clip-on Flip up Metal Clip Sunglasses Lenses Glasses Unbreakable Driving Fishing Outdoor Sport
column13: Measure very carefully and imagine how these will sit on your eyeglasses before making a purchase.
column14: Although this product is accurately described with regard to the dimensions, they are very misleading. Depending on the construction of your eyeglasses they may not fully cover the lenses - they do not on mine. I carefully measured my lenses and found they were very close to the size of this product. However, the construction of my frames and the hing part of this product, caused them to sit very high on the frame, This caused almost a full 1/4 inch, at the bottom of my lenses, to remain uncovered by the product. In addition to a curved piece holding my glasses together, there is a top bar. This bar  running across the top of the frame, prevented the product from sitting low enough to cover that bottom 1/4 inch. My suggestion is to buy a pair of clip on sun glasses in a store, where you can experiment to make sure they will cover your lenses completely.

column6: Timberland PRO Women's Renova Slip-On
column14: I have been wearing the same pair for just over a year. The outer sole and insole are finally starting to break apart so I am on the search for my next pair of work shoes. Given that I walk holes in most of my work shoes in six months or less I am tempted to buy these again. The high quality leather is one of the reasons they have lasted a year, I'm sure, but it doesn't make for a very breathable shoe. This is a problem when you spend 40+ hours a week running around sweating in them (I wear them as a waitress in a high volume restaurant). I've never had a problem with foot odor before, but I have to apply Odor Eaters everyday to these shoes. For that reason, and all the squeaking they do for the first month or so, I have been looking elsewhere. I do find them quite comfortable. My feet are wide with a high arch and they are a little tight, though I believe it keeps my feet from swelling and contributes to their comfort. All and all one of the most comfortable, longest lasting work shoes I've ever owned. May end up purchasing them again.

column6: New Balance Men's MT510 Trail Trail Running Shoe
column14: I am another long-time (10+ years) user of New Balance shoes who finds that the 510v2 shoe doesn't fit my feet. The toe-box is generally too small, much smaller than other New Balance models that I wear regularly. The size differences seem random. I normally wear a 10.5 wide, which didn't fit me at all.  The 11 x-wide size was wide enough, but so short that my toes curl at the end. So I tried an 11.5 x-wide, which was long enough, but as painfully narrow as a medium width shoe. So if you've found a size that fits you properly in this model, that's great, but don't depend on the size of this shoe to determine a proper fit. I've given up trying to find a size that fits in the 510 model.

column13: At 4 months of use, the soles have come completely off of the upper. Worst boots I have ever owned.
column14:
These are awful boots. I am a mechanic, so I'm not very hard on boots. A pair of cheap boots usually lasts at least one year on me. These did not survive 4 months.

When I first received them I swore one was built slightly different than the other. I have had no fitment issues between feet prior to buying these boots. On my right foot the boot presses up against my pinkie toe, and it feels as if my pinkie toe lays on top of the leather instead of the insole. The left foot felt fine at first. They are made in China, so it's not surprising.

Now that we are at the 4 month mark, they have completely fallen apart. The soles are completely falling off. Pieces of broken plastic are falling out from the sole as well. These are the worst boots I have ever owned. I have owned boots that cost half as much and lasted twice as long.

column6: Sesto Meucci Women's Gabys 982491 Flat
column13: Comfort, Style, and Durability in One Package
column14: I own multiple pairs of Sesto Meuccis, so I know how they fit my foot.  My feet are narrow in width, narrow in heel, with a high instep.  The best features of this shoe are the padded heel (comfortable grip), arch support (so my feet don't get tired), side-gore expansion (for my high instep), and shock-absorbing footbed (durability, walk all day).  In Sestos, I wear an 8N; in other quality brands, an 8.5N.  Please note this applies to Sestos made in Italy.  Like other manufacturers, sometimes they offshore their production - this results in sizing differences, so I look for the ones made in Italy only.

column6: Susan Zee-0678
column14: I ordered this product back in April as a birthday present for my mother. At first she absolutely loved the purse. I ordered the black version and it had plenty of pockets and she never have one that large before so it was even better. Now I understand with any handbag/purse there will be normal wear and tear from everyday use, but this bag started falling apart less than 90 days of use. The material actually started flaking/pealing and the seams were even coming undone and even the little metal pieces broke off. My mom was never rough with the bag; if she goes shopping it sits in the cart, at work it sits in her locker, and at home its sits in her room. This has never happened to any of my handbags even the cheaper ones that I've purchased at stores like walmart or claires. I would not recommend this purse to anyone looking to use it for more than 30 days. After contacting Amazon they informed me they usually send a replacement for defective products, but the black bag is currently out of stock and they will be issuing me a full refund.

column14: I wore these shoes 2 times (1st time 2 hours around the house) and the second time I started to hear a small weird sound while walking. The worst part is that I bought these in April but  I did not use them or even take them out of their box until July and now I do not have the option to send them back or get a refund or even contact the seller to inform of this. A  friend of mine told me that it is possible that I got knockoffs instead of original shoes because mine say "Made in China" and other Adidas Springbalde are supposed to be from Vietnam. column13: Invasion of the Giant Cyclops Burgers!
column14:
I LOVE these shoes, but be warned, they run at least a full size too large. I read the reviews and wasn't sure if I should buy my size or a size down. I decided to go for my size, figuring a full size down would be too small, and thought I could use a thick insole if necessary. WRONG! They were much too big, so I packed them up and sent them right back. Gladly, the return was free and I got my money back right away. I couldn't wait to order the size 6, but they were still a little bit too big, so I popped in my insoles (they are clear so you can still see the french fries inside!) and had my husband make an extra hole in the ankle strap. Now, I can wear them out and walk around with no problems. They are super-cute, sturdy, and are actually pretty comfortable.

The only reason I gave them 4 stars instead of 5 is because of the sizing. Honestly, I ordered, returned, re-ordered, and received them in less than a week so it wasn't a big deal, but was disappointed that they run so huge.

If you're thinking about getting these, they are truly awesome shoes and I definitely recommend them, but be sure to order a size down. You won't be disappointed, but you *will* be tall. :)

column6: Dr. Martens Men's Maclean Slip On Loafers
column13: These are very comfortable to wear
column14:
Picked these up for under $40 and figured for that price I would take a chance. Not really big of slip on heavy leather shoes, but these have changed my mind. These are very comfortable to wear, easy to slip on and head out the door. They are also very comfortable to wear around the house because they kick off real easy when reclined back in my recliner....though they do thump pretty loud when they hit the floor. The loud thump doesn't really bother me, it's the look I get from my wife when they hit the floor the does get my attention.
The leather is a nice thick grade material, stitching appears to be the quality of what you would expect from Dr Marten. Not sure the sole will last as long as the original DM shoes did, but they sure look like they have many years of service to offer.
And of course since DM does not offer 1/2 size shoes or boots you have to round up to the nearest full size and adjust then with sock thickness. However this also offers just a little more width for those with a little wider foot.

column6: adidas Men's Adicross SL Golf Shoe
column14:
Got a few rounds in this summer with these and initial impressions are very good. Did I mention I walk...?

I'm a fairly large fella and felt plenty comfortable after walking 18 in these. My feet felt supported and comfortable during and after the round. I dont think I could ever go back to traditional golf shoes.

If you play multiple rounds a week you may need a lace-up shoe but for casual and weekend golfers, I'd recommend giving these a shot. I love them and have made these my go-to shoe.

Stability is good which surprised me for a slip-on. I expected a lot of slip and slide during my swing (I avg around 100mph swing). That's a decent amount of torgue held firmly and confidently in place.

It's more important to get the right size for a slip-on to ensure the best stability, obviously. I typically wear 11.5 in Adidas and got these in 11 and that worked great for me.

Bottom line... Very comfortable and perfect for my style and weekend rounds.

Keep'em tween the trees!

column6: adidas Performance Men's Ultra Boost M Running Shoe
column13: Great Running shoe, but are tight
column14: I have been marathon training in the Adidas Ultra Boost shoes since they were first introduced. They are, by far, the most cushioned long-distance shoe I've ever run in. I've run marathons in several other brands, but I like these so much, I've ordered a second pair, as my first pair have reached the end of their operational life. The proprietary foam holds up well.   Issues I have is that you have to be careful how tight to tie them, otherwise the upper will dig into your foot. But the entire upper fits like a thick sock, so you really don't have to tie the shoes down tight. They also lack the toe box that most running companies use now. So if you have wide feet, these will be very tight around the forefoot.   The thin rubber sole is also a problem. The nubs wear down after only a hundred miles, and then the shoes become very slick in wet conditions. I do hope Adidas revises these soles, but it's too late in my training to switch to another shoe, so I've ordered another pair of ultra boost. I can't see the soles lasting 300 miles safely.    they also seem to run small. I generally wear size 13 running shoes (size 12 daily wear), but with Adidas, I always need to order 14s. So be aware of that when buying. But Adidas has a great return/exchange policy, so if you buy too small, there is a "no questions asked" return.

column14: I have chronic low back pain.  My chiropractor recommended these shoes.  Usually within 15 mins of waking, it starts aching and goes downhill from there.  I have a morning routine of stretches and exercises just to get my back in shape for the day.  She told me to put these shoes on first thing and it has made a big difference.  So far, wearing these shoes seems to be the only morning routine I need.  I ordered 3 other pairs so I don't look like Grandpa in my plaid shorts and black dress shoes out walking the dog, but I have to say, if my back feels good, I really don't care what it looks like.  The good news is that these are attractive shoes and it seems that the more I walk, the better my back.  Usually, the opposite is true.  I wear a 7.5M and the shoe fits comfortably.  There's enough room that if I wanted to wear a regular sock in the winter, there's room.  I am so thankful to have found these shoes.  Anyone who has back pain knows how it can really get in the way of life.  Very thankful for these shoes.

column6: Premium Hard Eyeglasses Case for Maximum Glasses Security | Bonus Cleaning Cloth
column14:
I've worn eyeglasses ever since I've been in the 6th-grade (1993 to be exact) and every pair I've owned always comes with a free eyecase holder, which most of the time the cases are made from cheap plastic. I was well aware that you could purchase eyecases separately, but I never thought about getting one. Well, that is until I received the Men's Eyecase Holder to test out and review.

What can I say about the Men's Eyecase Holder? It's pretty durable with a metal-bodied and a metal hinge. It also features a soft black velvet lining in the inside, so it'll protect your glasses from getting damaged. Along with the eyecase, you also get a cleaning cloth for your glasses. Overall, I do like the Men's Eyecase Holder as it's made from better materials than the previous eyecases I've received when I purchased my glasses.

*Disclaimer - I received a complimentary sample in exchange for my honest review. All opinions are my own.

column6: Tingley Mens 1400 Pull-on Work Overboot
column13: Great for rain saturated ground yard work!
column14: I've been using these boots for 3 summers now and they are still very functional.  The heavy rains in Florida flood most of my yard every summer ... got a record 3" of rain yesterday ... and I could not do anything in the yard without these boots.  I keep an old pair of heavy duty clogs in the boots so that I can just slip the boots on and off easily.  My clogs are a women's size 10 wide and fit into the XL boot nice and snug as you don't want to be slipping out of these boots while you are sinking into the rain saturated ground.  There is a heavy sole on the clog and this makes it easy to use a shovel with the boots over the clogs.  No issues w/ the boot tearing.  I recommend wearing socks because the black rubs off on the exposed heel skin.  I wear my socks over my long knit pants and have no trouble getting the boots on and off.  I often sink to the ankle in these boots and my feet stay dry.  The only time I get wet is when some water gets in through a slush through the top of the boot.  Overall, these boots have been great and I highly recommend them for this purpose.

I'll have to remember to update this review after I do a workout in them, because I've discovered many people are saying that this shoe excels specifically for workouts but not much else.

In summary, the shoes run about 1/8 inch (half size) shorter and the shoe rim is uncomfortable on the ankles.

column6: Hi-Tec Men's Fusion Low WP Multisport Trail Running Shoe
column14: These shoes were purchased for my 2nd Camino de Santiago (Camino Frances) that I just completed this summer.  The Camino de Santiago is an approximate 500 mile hike (790 km.) that starts in the Pyrenees in St. Jean Pied de Port and finishes in Santiago de Compostela Spain. The terrain varies widely from asphalt to boulderish steep mountain paths.  For my 1st Camino in 2012, I had used Keen Zion's that I had tried to buy again, but were discontinued. The Keen's that replaced them were not as reviewed as well so I decided to try something different.  After trying out a pair of Patagonia's that I returned because they didn't feel right after a couple of break-in uses, I came across these Hi-Tec at a local DSW.  I wore them a few times to work and they felt good and broke in nicely.  I decided these were it for Camino 2015.  In the time I used them, the shoes did well despite a couple of normal customary blisters.  They did even better after I improved on the insole, purchasing a much more cushiony insole 141 miles into the hike (228 km.)  After that the shoes felt even better.  I believe I may have gone on without any more blisters after the insole replacement.  Where the shoes became a HUGE disappointment is when I noted at the 211 mile part of the hike (340 kms.) that the shoes were becoming separated from the sole!!!  Needless to say, I was very worried (especially without duct tape!) and I knew that I would have to replace the shoes.  Replacing shoes mid-hike is every trekkers nightmare since they would need to be broken in and the potential for new foot problems becomes greater.  The next big city I was told that would have hiking shoes was Leon at 7 days away!  After 3 days, I arrived in a decent sized town that actually had some time type of selection and I was able to get new shoes.  I bought some type of European brand that I will not talk about since this review is for the Hi-Tec's I specifically bought for this trip.  BUT those shoes made it for the remaining 320 miles plus the extra 50 to get to Finesterre. (530 km total), AND they still look like they could handle another Camino!!  Based on my experience with this brand on my hike, I will never buy any of their products again and will stick to more well-known and respected brands when doing a long hike of any magnitude again. A shoe that is bought for a hike like this should last for at least as long as it was intended.  My 2012 Keen's are still in service.

column6: Vasque Men's Eriksson Gore-Tex Boot
column14:
I've put about 150 miles on my Erikssons, mostly on pavement, with some very rough trails mixed in. Generally, the boots fit well, have excellent traction, and are comfortable. Once they were broken in (word to wise: don't tighten the ankles too much for at least 20 miles or you'll regret it), I headed up to Lake Tahoe to climb Mount Tallac with my son. This is a steep trail with 3500 elevation change that travels about 9.5 miles up and back. It has long sections of scree and tallus. Looking up at one very steep section of scree switchbacks made me feel like I was climbing into Mordor. Really hard on the feet. I did not have the boots tied tight enough early on and this combined with the heat and tough trail gave me some sore toes even though I had plenty of wiggle room initially. Some reviewers have commented on the shoes having a slightly narrow toe box, but this hike made me realize that it's not the last per se, but the fact that the boot leather in the toe box pulls in when tied tight after the boots have been broken in. My toes were more sore on top than the bottom, though I got no blisters. My solution has been to tie a square knot in the laces after the second loop, which releases the tension on the laces below and prevents the toe box walls from being pulled in when tied tight. I'll be hiking the High Sierra Loop out of Tuolumne Meadows in Yosemite in September, so I'm crossing my fingers that this lacing technique does the trick. See http://www.backpacker.com/view/photos/skills-photos/beginner-basics-corrective-boot-tying/#bp=0/img3. Otherwise, the boots were very comfortable.

I do have small concerns regarding durability, as the toe cap on my left boot developed a small separation from the rubber rand during the Mount Tallus hike. I'll try to glue this back down so it does not get worse. To be fair, I did stub my toe multiple times, so some cosmetic damage would normal. But this separation was disappointing after just one hike regardless of howtough it was.

I went for these boots over the well-reviewed St. Elias model because of the better leather and small weight difference, and I'm glad I did. I have a touch of Plantar Fasciitis, so I'm hoping the added stability of these boots, combined with Superfeet Carbon insoles, helps. My foot did fairly well on this brutal hike, but I was feeling it some that night, though not so much the next morning. This said, I'm also experimenting with the trail runner approach.

column14:
I have been wearing Asics - exclusively - for 40 years.
in recent years, i have owned 5 pairs of Asics Gel Intensity shoes.
They, like all Asics, are a great shoe.

i work out 3x a week - always indoors.
i don't run.

i purchased my Intensity 3s in April - by June, the sole was separating from the shoe.

This is my second set of Asics Intensity 3s - i had the exact same problem with the first pair. When i called Asics regarding the first pair, i got the party line - send them to us - we'll inspect them - then we'll make a determination.....i'm sure you guys get it.

fortunately, i bought my second pair from Amazon - they don't need to inspect them - they immediately emailed a free shipping label - you know the rest.

so now - i'm looking for a cross fit shoe - i love this shoe - it fits great - does what it's supposed to do but it's not that well made. i really hate to leave Asics.

just my two cents.

column13: Great Shoe, didn't work for me... wish it had
column14:
As a teacher with plantar fasciitis, I am always on the look out for stylish shoes that are comfortable AND offer great support. I have to say that I loved the look of the shoe and feel of the shoe- it has nice soft leather uppers with plenty of room in the toe box without being "clunky", and I really wanted to keep it. The shoe fit nicely, even with my orthotics inserted. There were two things caused concern for me: 1. My orthotic made the right shoe squeak with every step. I can't be walking around my classroom with squeaky shoes.... :) 2.I know that these shoes have special technology to give support in the arch- I just didn't feel the support I need, even with my orthotics inserted. I suspect that if I had worn them all day in the classroom that my feet would have been very unhappy by the end of the day. As a teacher all day support is essential.

If you have issue-free feet I imagine that this would be a wonderfully comfortable shoe. But sadly, I had to return these shoes, thank goodness for free returns!

column13: these are absolutely beautiful shoes and I love them
column14: Firstly, these are absolutely beautiful shoes and I love them. They look very elegant and sleek, and also are of good quality by what I can tell thus far. I have not worn them at my wedding yet but am looking forward to it. Now on to the important stuff: sizing. I normally wear between 7.5 and 8.5 depending on the type of shoe. column13: Good price point, would buy again.
column14:
I have to say the insoles these boots ship with were horrible. Hard, ill fitting, and just terrible. I couldn't wear them more than 1 hour. I hit a specialty shoe store nearby, and bought some new insoles that fit my feet better. After that, I started putting the miles on these boots. I hash (walking, with attempts to run), backback, ruck, hike, and camp. They did great. Paired with some ace bandages for ankle support and FITS socks for wicking/warmth, and they were great performers. Point in case: I recently went on a Hash/camping trip with cross country trails, and a float trip at the end of one of these trails. These boots went through creeks and drained really well. I had no problem with traction except for one instance on a mossy climb where my boot slipped. 40 - 50% grades gave me no traction issues, and during the float trip they did wonders giving me traction on the slick river rocks, drained really well when I took breaks on the side of the river, and were supportive during the trail that went through a swamp where I was mucking through knee and thigh deep mud.

A little bit about me: I'm 6'2", 370 lbs, and I have horrible feet issues from being overweight.

4/5 due to insoles, and I which they were taller than their advertised 8"

column13: Great Shoes, an Improvement on the V3
column14:
I have been wearing New Balance shoes for years since I have always been happy with the quality and fit of their shoes. I wore V3 Minimus shoes for the last year and a half as casual, running, and weightlifting shoes and they held up alright with some ripping in the mesh parts. I just purchased the V4 version and the build quality looks much higher than it's older counterpart.

Some Improvements:
-The top and sides that used to be mostly mesh are now reinforced better than they used to be
-The tread feels better when walking around and running
-I got the bright blue (which looks awesome by the way) as opposed to the more boring black

All in all, awesome shoes that I would recommend to anyone lifting or running!

column14:
Stylish looking and seem to be high quality at first.

I'm updating this review because I am extremely skeptical of the UV blocking claims. I wore these for a day of driving nad runnig errands. At the end of the day my eyes were in physical pain and I was extremely light sensitive. I believe by (a) dilating your eye, because they're quite dark and (b) allowing UV rays to pass through, these do more damages than no glasses at all. Your dilated pupil allows more UV to reach your retina and it hurts like a bastard at the end of the day. I would not recommend these glasses. I believe the UV coating is not accurate based on my experience.

column6: Grasshoppers Women's Janey Twill Lace-Up Sneaker
column14:
I purchased size 7 1/2 M in the Light Khaki color. It's a well-made shoe for light everyday wear. The fabric is light, crisp with a slight silkiness to it and I think it would wear well and repel dirt somewhat. I wanted to keep the shoes but they were a bit too long and gap somewhat when I walked. I don't feel the 7 medium would work after reading the reviews for my particular foot shape. ALso I think the 7 narrow would be too tight across the top of my foot. I purchased another very similar styleGH's in a light grey tweed fabric and I will be reordering those in 7 medium because they didn't gap and felt softer around the ankle due to the style of padding. For the right sized foot, these shoes would be excellent. They are nice shoes for the price. I wouldn't recommend for athletic use or hard walking on pavement.

12-17-15 - I have found the Grasshoppers sneakers to be unsafe for me because the soles are not completely rubber as they state in the online description. I have slipped and nearly fallen when wearing them. There are a some very small strips or circles of rubber material, but mostly a hard plasticized material which is totally slippery on tile or other smooth floor surfaces that may have a few drops of moisture on the surface. Therefore I have reduced the stars from 4 to 2.

column13: The best sandals in the world!
column14:
I love these sandals! I'm on my second pair and eyeing a third, I'm never going back to other flip flops again! They have dressier styles too & no one can ever tell I'm wearing orthopedics (which is good because I'm 30), thanks to the two-color design on the sole to camouflage the thickness.

These shoes have saved my previously injured ankle & my ability to go for walks! Other sandals without support would make it swell up again & I'd be in so much pain & laid up for days. Since getting these shoes, my ankle never swells & I can walk miles in them!

The shoes run a little big - normally I wear an 8.5/9 and in these I wear an 8. They also arrived really tight in the straps in both my pairs that I have - but don't worry they are designed that way. After an hour or two of just walking around the house, the straps stretch to fit my feet perfectly.

I convinced my coworker with knee pain after a sports injury knee surgery to try a pair because her knee continued to bother her. Now she won't wear any other sandals - these are as good if not better than sneakers!

column6: Womens Cotton Mary Jane Shoes Ballerina Ballet Flats Shoes (11, YELLOW 114)
column13: Cheap burst of color for costume
column14: I bought a pair of these shoes to go with a costume. Mine are yellow with a yellow sole, though the picture makes the bottom look almost light tan (it's not, it's a half shade lighter yellow than the shoe itself). They are what I expected looking through reviews, and I am satisfied with them for my purposes. I did NOT have issues with strong chemical odors as some have reported, though that may be due to others' sensitivities or perhaps a bad pair. There was a faint smell of "newness" like new plastic- likely from the bag it came in- but it went away within an hour. I will need to buy some kind of inserts to support my arches since I'll be doing a fair bit of walking, but I bought these knowing I'd need to make that extra expense. As for fit, I wear a size 11 regular width and purchased the same. They fit just fine out of the package bare footed with enough wiggle room to comfortably wear a pair of socks. If you are between a regular and a wide width, I would say you can fit them but maybe expect a bit of "breaking them in" time. Color wise I would say the picture is a little lighter than the actual shade I received. The color is like a marigold, light sunflower yellow (kind of like the Simpsons' skintone) so if you're looking for a vibrant "true" yellow you might be disappointed, but I was actually pleasantly surprised since that worked for me.

column13: Very pretty, very comfy, but do not last AT ALL
column14: We bought these shoes on April 10 of this year, and it's now August 2. So it's been about 3.5 months during a hot North Carolina summer (which means very little sneaker wearing). She's about as far from a tomboy as possible (I have to make her go outside, and she almost always wears crocs when she does) and the "grass" where she played at school is that high-end artificial grass, so it doesn't get muddy or gross out there. In conditions like these, I'd expect these shoes to look decent after 15-20 wears. I'm not expecting them to look perfect, of course. But they look awful! column13: Birkenstock Papillio Tabora Sandals -- Lightness - Black . . . BEST SANDALS I'VE EVER OWNED!!
column14: I bought these sandals many years ago, when they were branded as Birki, not Papillio, which I guess makes them five years old at least. (Papillio introduced them in 2010 in this color.) It took a few days to get them adjusted satisfactorily that I can recall, but from then on I've never looked back!  The hallmark awesome Birkenstock footbed is there, with it's arch support, toe ridge and so so comfortable suede lining.  The sandals have been on my feet in almost all weather conditions -- well, except ice and snow! I wear them outdoors from March to mid November because they are so comfortable, and indoors all year round.  Now, after hundreds if not thousands of miles of wear, the small strap part of the toe "ring" has started to split on both shoes where it meets the sole right between my toes. And the cork sole is doing the same, precisely where the small toe strap meets the sole. It hasn't yet split the whole way across the sole. The good news here is that the EVA (final) layer of the sole is still intact -- no splits whatsoever. Although the "Birk" impressions which were to be seen here and there on the new soles are now but a memory, there is still plenty of wear left in them, and while the toe strap has stretched a bit and started to split, my Birkis are still perfectly wearable, even after five years! Today I bought another pair (although the Lightness range has long since been discontinued), in anticipation of the forthcoming unhappy day when my toe straps finally complete their split from my soles! To sum up:  I highly recommend these sandals to anyone thinking about buying a pair. You may need a few days to get used to this style, even if you're used to wearing toe post sandals, as I was, and you may even get a few small blisters, but persevere with them. It will be SO worth it!

column6: Cliffs by White Mountain Women's Pacey Oxford
column14: I have to admit I got these because of the "aggressive sole" as the details say. I love shoes with good traction and these are perfect. The sole is a very noticeable part of the shoe and makes them a bit more stompy than if they didn't have such deep lugs. I love walking from building to building at work in them, first because they are very comfortable, and second because I don't have to concern myself with where I step. When I take my favorite path across the grass I know the treads will grip in the muddy patches that I find there, so I don't have to step over or around them. When I am in our messy cafeteria I can just let my soles land where they may--on spilled drinks, a dropped breakfast, old french fries--the sharp edges of the treads bite in and grip. Aggressively! The best part is that they leave their marks when I do that. I always leave a mark in the mud, and often track the food I walk on across the cafeteria floor. The day after I got the shoes I walked through a big patch of spilled macaroni and cheese, and it tracked for many steps because a lot of it stuck in the deep crevices of the lugs. My lunchmates joked they found where I was sitting because of the yellow tracks I left across the room!

column6: Sperry Women's H20 Escape Bungee Water Sneaker
column13: The shoes drain very well once they are submerged in water and are super grippy on the bottom
column14:
I purchased these to wear while white water rafting in TN. I normally wear a 9.5 or 10, so I purchased these in a 10, and they fit well and fairly snug across the top of my foot, but not uncomfortably so. I was confident that they would not come off my feet while rafting. We had many outdoor activities planned for the week vacation in TN, and boy was I impressed with these shoes and also ended up wearing them ziplining, all day at Dollywood Amusement Park and on 2 hikes to waterfalls in the Smokey Mountain Park.

The shoes drain very well once they are submerged in water and are super grippy on the bottom. Both of our hikes were moderate in difficulty and were on trails that had many small and large rocks, tree roots, streams, and mud. I also wore them in and out of the rocks and running water near the falls and felt very secure that I would not slip despite some quite steep descents and climbs both on land and in water. They are not as supportive as regular tennis shoes and I did have a slightly sore lower back after our longer hike and our all day at Dollywood, but as much as put these shoes through, I was thoroughly pleased and would purchase this brand in the future. I don't normally submit product reviews online, but I was so happy with these shoes, I had to submit this review.

column14: My very first purchase of Sperry Angelfish shoes was in the leopard sequins print.  I ordered them from a well-known shoe retailer and not having ever owned Sperry's before I went with my regular sizing at a 5.  When they arrived I tried them on to find that they are really quite loose.  They slip a lot on my heel leaving blisters.  This is my fault though since I didn't know how these shoes ran in size.  Since this initial purchase I have a second pair of Sperrys.  This pair I tried on in store for a good fit.  I ended up getting a size 2.5 in kids size.  They were a little snug at first but stretched out to the perfect size and now they are my favorite shoes.  So my best advice would be to try these on in a store or be sure if you are ordering them online that there are free exchanges/returns.

column6: Kenneth Cole Reaction Men's Cross The Desert Slip-On Loafer
column14: Considering the low price, I find the shoe is great for paring with jeans for an evening of dining out or conversation with friends. I don't hold any expectation that these will be my go-to everyday shoes. These shoes are made in India. The workmanship is passable. The outside leather is soft and they are comfortable; almost like slippers. But, there's little cushioning or support for your aches or the bottom of your feet. I installed a pair of double thickness Dr. Scholl's cushions and that did the trick for me. If you have pes planus (flat feet) or plantar tendinitis you might want to skip these shoes. If you have foot  problems or you need these shoes to stand-up to daily wear and walking activity, you'll likely be disappointed. If you intend to wear them occasionally and only for a few hours at at time, they'll do just fine....especially considering the low  price. By the way, this supplier has nearly doubled the price since I purchased these shoes in July 2015.

column6: Fila Women's Memory Fresh 2 Running Shoe
column14: I bought these shoes to wear to Disney World.  We have gone in the past and not having the right shoes at Disney World can be a disaster.  I am a big woman (270 lbs) and very active so I have to have shoes that will support my ankles and feet.  These shoes were amazing.  We were at the parks all day (17 hours) for 5 days and my feet and legs were fine.  According to my pedometer (calibrated) I averaged around 22,000 steps each day and I had no pain or soreness at all!  Frankly it was amazing.  If someone my size can wear these shoes and be on her feet all day and still be ready for more, they will work for almost anyone.  I should also mention that I usually have problems with my heels and arches; my trainer says it is something about the way my feet hit the ground when I jog or power walk; but I have not experienced that issue since buying these shoes.  (Not sure why; but if it fixes the issue I suppose I do not need an explanation.)

column6: Sof Sole Thin Fit Medium Arch Lightweight Low Volume Shoe Insole
column13: Exceptional Cushioning In Tight Spaces -- Easily Worth It To Be More Comfortable
column14: I'm amazed how much cushion you get out of such a thin insole. In most of my shoes I replace the OEM with either the Sorbothane UltraSole (w/o arch support) or the Sof Sole Airr Lightweight; so now I am uncomfortable if I don't have that level of cushion (a very "first world" kind of problem). However, both require a significant amount of extra clearance in order to fit right. I tried this "ultra thin" version of the Sof Sole recently in a pair of Patagonia Drifters that need to be pretty snug because they are meant (and used in my case) for hiking. They fit perfectly when swapped for the stock (read: cheap uncomfortable cardboard) insole and feel almost as good as the much thicker Airr or UltraSole. I have pretty low arches and avoid replacement insoles with more than very minimum arch support; so these are exactly what I needed in every respect. I am really impressed and they certainly exceeded my expectations for such a thin insole. One other discovery: if these are still a little too thick for your situation, the even thinner option is the Spenco Rx Comfort. One answer on its page says they are only 3/32" thick. They are also perfectly flat from heel to toe; so there are no bubbles, bumps or arch "golf balls" to make things tight in one particular area. They don't provide the cushion of this amazing "ultra thin" insole, but they help considerably while requiring the absolute minimum amount of clearance to fit. So between those two options I am able to "enhance" every shoe I wear regularly. When you consider how much you pay for quality shoes these days, the extra investment seems reasonable-- and if it encourages you to keep them longer because they are still comfortable, you actually save some money in the long run. So that's my observation and experience with these super thin alternatives to their much thicker big brothers-- exceptional cushioning in tight spaces and easily worth the $15 investment.

column6: Newton Running Mens Gravity Blue/Red Sneaker 9 D (M)
column14:
You think you're being healthy doing the urban running thing, but those cartilage cutlets that keep your joints from screaming are vanishing to the clomp of flat-footed impact. If you run the right way, your joints can remain intact; or so goes the concept of minimalist running.

Newton Gravity are a form of minimalist running shoe. They make you plant on your foot's ball (yes, they have balls), between your toes and arch. Like running barefooted, you absorb force through muscles, particularly the calves and hallucis.

Practically speaking, people new to these shoes will feel sore. But after a few weeks, your muscles will adapt and your joints will thank you. Here's to your health!

column6: Reebok Men's Nano 4.0 Cross-Training Shoe
column13: Awesome shoes with little arch support
column14:
I'm fairly new to Crossfit but have been weight training all of my life (I'm a 44 yr old male). After joining the Crossfit gym and climbing a few ropes I quickly determined that I needed appropriate shoes for this new sport. Love the 4mm heal drop and the shoes fit me perfectly. They are very comfortable for Olympic lifting as well as Metcons. I have ran up to 2 miles in these shoes and they are adequate for this task as well.

These shoes do NOT provide much arch support. I have a huge arch and have suffered for over a year now with plantar fasciitis. These shoes are fairly flat which made them a perfect match for my orthotic insoles. I could NOT wear these out of the box due to the lack of arch support. No way. However, once I removed the thin insole and replaced with my own, the shoes are awesome.

I also want to add that my wife and my daughter both have a pair of these shoes. They have normal feet without ginormous arches and they both wear them out of the box and love them as well.

column6: FRYE Josie Backpack
column13: A classy backpack (or a lovely purse) in beautifully finished leather...
column14:
i have several Frye handbags in a couple of different styles/sizes and I am very impressed with them--they look great and are very versatile and durable--one or the other of them is used every day (I like to switch them every month or so...). I don't really have the budget to purchase items such as this at the regular price (quite a splurge!, but when they go on sale, I think they are a great deal--gorgeous as well as practical--and last for years with just a modicum of care). I also have a backpack in a rustic tan leather made by the same company that I use during the academic year for books and folders and it has also worked out very well. So, although I can't really say I needed another backpack I had still been keeping an eye on this one and was constantly checking availability and price just in case a great deal popped up on a black one...but before that happened, I received one as a gift!
I haven't used it much yet, since I just got it, but so far it is great! It is quite large and holds a lot but is still easy to carry (I also find it simple to position on my back, so I am more likely to use it correctly, rather than just slinging it over one shoulder as I often do with other backpacks) either as a hand-held purse/handbag or as a backpack and the detachable backpack straps make it versatile (remove them and you have a very nice, large tote-sized bag that zippers closed. One feature that some people may not like is the position of the zipper--like the Josie purse, it is located at the front of the bag, and not at the top so this might affect how easy it is to pack very large or bulky items...but I don't carry anything that big so not a problem for me, and I like the way it looks with this configuration. I also like the pocket at the front of the bag--my keys and glasses are easy to get to and it looks buckled but is held by a magnetic snap.

column6: KISS GOLD(TM) Dual-Use Sporty Nylon Cellphone Pouch Mini Shoulder Bag Wristlet
column14:
This review is being made two days after I received the cellphone bag.

I ordered this because I now regularly carry a personal and business cell phone. It can be awkward carrying both, plus pad and pencil when wandering around at work and going to meetings. So, I looked for something that could hold both comfortably. Additional, like this week, sometimes I am also the 'on-call' person for after hours emergencies and need to carry a third phone with me at all minutes of the day (missing a call is just not allowed).

The picture I uploaded shows all the things that I was able to easily fit into this bag: iPhone 5 in Otter box (7cm x 13.6cm x 1.6cm), Samsung Galaxy 6 in Otter box (15.5cm x 8.9cm x 1.7cm), Samsung Galaxy Note III (8.5cm x 15.7cm x 0.7cm), a small note book (8.9cm x 13.9cm x 0.8cm).

The Samgung G6 and notepad fit in back pocket, the Samsung GNIII in middle pocket and the iPhone in the front pocket.

If the iPhone had been in a smaller case, the front pocket could be closed over it.

Without the notepad in the back, both of the Samsung pockets are closable. With the notepad the zippers could be closed, but it put a lot of stress on the seems on the back pocket.

I was also able to add an iPod Touch (no case) to the front pocket.

With the strap snugged up, this hangs just right under the arm on the side, with easy access to each of the phones.

It's early days yet to say how the bag will hold up over time. But, so far, it is exactly what I need. I'll try to remember to update this when I can provide good evaluation (one way or another) of the basic sturdiness.

column6: Twisted Women's Bonnie Casual Fashion Boat Shoe
column13: This will be the most helpful review.
column14: Favorite shoes! I bought one pair several months ago and just bought another pair. They fit wonderfully. I'm a size 9 normally and these size 9's fit perfectly. I have somewhat wide feet but don't have to order shoes wide, for the most part. I don't wear them with socks and they don't rub anywhere. They're surprisingly soft. I need arch support or my feet ache and these give me just enough support.  The don't slip at the heal and the little laces give it just the perfect fit. The laces wrap all the way around the shoe, so when you pull them tight, you can really feel they fit snug or loosen them if you have wider feet. The fabric is so soft. Just like any pair of shoes you were without socks, the bacteria from your sweaty feet will make your feet and shoes smell. So I've washed them 3 times in my washer with bleach, detergent and oxy-clean. I then let them air dry. Not only do they not stink after that but they fit just the same if not a little better. I bought a white pair the first time and the gold/white pair the second time, so I used regular bleach but you can use color-safe bleach if you bought shoes with color. I love these shoes. I wear them with my work clothes and casual clothes. They go with everything and look so cute. I get compliments on them all the time. I'll be sad when the snow comes and I can't wear them until spring again. :-)

column13: Not the best, not the worst.   Well made for the price.
column14:
Good price, decent boot. I like the eyelet construction, using washers on the interior side. They are fairly light compared to some of my other boots, and there's really nothing overtly wrong with them. But the sole feels like it's going wear down pretty quickly (which does however make them a little more shock absorbent I think) and the shank/midsole portion of the boot is a little weak. I wouldn't want to be on a round-rung ladder for too many hours with these.

The fit is right on size, and there was really no break in discomfort. Of course they felt better after a few dozen days of wearing them, that's how leather boots work, but they weren't bad straight out of the box.

Hooray for oblique toe though! I wish more manufacturers would make them this shape.

column6: Borgasets Women's Genuine Leather Bifold Wallet Passport Purse
column14: I was a bit nervous about the quality of the wallet because of the very reasonable price. I was pleasantly surprised. The leather is very soft to the touch and is the color that I was expecting. It has lots of card slots which is why I chose this wallet over other options. There isn't a place for change, which could be a downside to some. There is a zippered slot inside the wallet, but with change inside it makes the wallet bulky. Personally, I prefer my change in a small coin purse anyways. It is tricky to get an ID in and out of the ID slot because there isn't a cutout in the plastic for your finger to push the card up. I anticipate that that problem will subside the more I use the wallet because the leather around the ID slot will soften. All in all, this wallet was exactly what I was looking for despite a couple of minor flaws. I would recommend it to others.

column13: Laughton - Very good, comfortable mens shoes!
column14:
Very good shoes!
Not sure why someone said these are more like "work" shoes. They definitely are NOT a work shoe. Also, they are not heavy as another reviewer suggested. Rather light weight, durable shoe and far from a "heavy" shoe. They are not "extremely" tight as someone said. They are a little snug/narrow. If in doubt get the wider width. They run true to size in length.
Whomever said the sole is big has no clue what a 'big' sole is. This is an average sole shoe. They are a bit loud when walking. The sole is semi-soft with insert pads on bottom.
The BORN Laughton are over all comfortable and very stylish, casual shoes that you could wear almost anywhere. Not a dress shoe.
I wouldn't consider them an all purpose shoe for Winter weather however.
BORN makes high quality, stylish, comfortable shoes. The BORN Axley are my favorite pair of shoes that I have. Get them. You wont regret it. More aggressive soles. I wear them daily.
BORN makes quality shoes that I WILL purchase again in the future. They stand behind their shoes. I know from experience.

column6: Oakley Men's SI 6 Military Boot
column13: No longer the quality SI boots you came to love
column14:
I've been buying and wearing Oakley SI boots since the '90's with generally positive experiences with design, workmanship, etc. However, this new boot is a stark turn in the wrong direction.
1) Boot seems designed for aesthetics now at the expense of basic field use characteristics. Case in point - Previous iterations of this boot had connecting fabric along the sides of the tongue which prevented dirt, pebbles, etc from entering the boot. New model has a minimal strip and now everything easily gets inside the boot. The new philosophy seems to be "who cares how it works/feels as long as it looks good."
2) Parts of the tread are weakly attached to the sole of the boot, a few hours of normal walking around and you are looking for the Gorilla Glue to re-attach a loose piece of waffle-shaped rubber to the bottom of your boot.
3) New upper material is thin and stiff, so although the boot is light, it isn't comfortable and doesn't feel rugged. The boot feels like you are wearing the cardboard box the boots came in and not the boot itself.
The success of this line of boot has spawned numerous competitors and Oakley might be a victim of their own success. Although they helped popularize this particular style of footwear, their decision to emphasize looks over usefulness has cost them at least one longtime customer.

column6: Inov-8 Men's FastLift 335 Cross-Training Shoe
column14:
These shoes are great! First of all, they fit as expected, which is always nice when ordering from Amazon. They also give you a good amount of heel lift, which is important for lifting shoes (it's the whole point!). The sole is quite stiff, and doesn't allow for much give, which maximizes your power transfer. The color combination looks good, in my opinion. If you're buying these for crossfit, I would say that running in these shoes isn't going to be the most comfortable, but it can be done. I haven't tried any other crossfit shoes before, so I can't say if another shoe would perform better for that. However, for lifting, it has really increased the amount of weight I can comfortably squat.

My only worry with these shoes is the same as what others have posted. The velcro seems to be attached at only a small point on the shoe, and I worry that it will come off some day. I don't wear these enough to have worn through that yet, but I can see why others had issues with it (which is why this is getting a 4/5 star rating).

Pros:
- Fits as expected
- Great color scheme
- Great for lifting (stiff and heel raise is perfect)

Cons:
- Longevity issues?

I would definitely recommend these overall!

column13: If you're looking for good quality work boots then Timberland Pro
column14: I've owned Cats in the past and they work well for light construction work around the house or landscaping but due to the lack of a proper safety toe these are not meant for anything such as medium to heavy construction work involving materials of 100lbs or more.  At the listed price of $60 ($40 off) these are priced more for someone wanting to make a fashion statement.  If you're looking for good quality work boots then Timberland Pro, Red Wings, and Wolverine work boots are your better bet and look into the composite safety toe models to save on weight and still maintain the same level of safety as a steel toe.  Timberland Pro line also has boots for specific trades such as welding with high temp soles.

column13: Sweet little shoe for a pool workout.
column14:
These shoes are a lifesaver for me. I do most of my exercise in a pool. The bottoms of my feet were getting roughed by the little irregularities at the bottom of the pool. I purchased these to combat that. Not only do they pad the bottom of my feet, they offer a bit of support and great traction for jogging in the shallow pool.

I generally wear a 6.5 or 7, but these size six are large enough with room to spare. The only issue I have is that the strap is not quite long enough to strap across my right foot, which is misshapen due to an accident. Also, reviews mentioned the insoles fall out, so I proactively purchased Shoe Goo and glued the insole in to prevent that.

Edited to add: I proactively glued down the insole, but then the fabric on top of the insole came off. This disappointments me greatly and I have changed my review from 4 to 3 stars.

column6: New Balance Women's WT110 Trail-Running Shoe
column14:
I bought these to work in, as I run a landscape company and I'm on my feet on different terrain every day. I have had several NB trail shoes, and got these because they are cheaper than my last pair of minimus trails. Overall they are good, but they slip in the heel on my right foot a bit, so my skin gets irritated there (but not quite a blister). The other thing is the seam by both my pinky toes rubs, and is uncomfortable there also. My feet aren't wide, but I am used to the wider toe box of the other trail shoes I've purchased. These are a little more narrow.
The tread is great, though, nice and rugged and I haven't slipped on dirt or grass. It has a nice amount of cushion, but not so much that it's overwhelming coming off of the minimus. However, I don't use these to run in, just work.

column13: Vibram FiveFingers are amazing shoes IF YOU LIKE BEING BAREFOOT
column14:
Vibram FiveFingers are amazing shoes IF YOU LIKE BEING BAREFOOT. I've been asked many times whether or not I'd recommend them when people have seen me wearing them, and my answer is always the same: if you like being barefoot, then get some, but if you don't like being barefoot then don't.

I'd definitely recommend getting toe socks for them too. "But you want to be like being barefoot," you respond, "and that's even LESS barefoot!" True, but first off, good toe socks won't add anything to the feel of the shoes (and are actually amazingly comfortable) plus they help prevent the FiveFingers from taking up the "nasty sweaty feet" smell by absorbing most of the sweat and stank from your feet that would've otherwise made a permanent home in your shoes.

The particular pair I got from Amazon were a bit longer than I was expecting, but considering the others I've gotten from elsewhere fit perfectly I'll just say it's the particular pair.

column6: Kenneth Cole REACTION Women's Glam-a-thon Flat Sandal
column14: I got the pewter color first.  Loved them so much and got so many compliments on them that I got the champagne color as well.  Both are very comfortable for me, but I should say that shoes with a significant built-in arch are not comfortable on me.  If you are looking for a noticeable arch support, this sandal may not be for you. (My feet are not flat, but I do pronate a bit.)  The "jewels" on these sandals are the most authentic and classy looking of all the jeweled sandals I've seen, even in the Kenneth Cole brand, which makes very nice sandals. They are finished well, have a very comfortable footbed, and a sort of felt-like material covering the rubber on the bottom which prevents the soles from marking the floors.  The footbed is the same material and color as the upper sandal and I believe it must be treated with an anti-microbial as I have no trouble with foot odor in these sandals.  I hope they never quit making these sandals!

column14: I really like these shoes, but have to give them a 3 rating because they hit at a spot on the side of foot where it caused a blister and got so bad that the blister popped as it continued rubbing untill i could go home. Even if they didn't rub against the side of my foot, they aren't comfortable for long term wear.  i also acknowledge the rubbing iss due to the shape of my foot, as i dont see many people having this problem, but i also have to point out that my other flats dont do this, so it was a real bummer. On the plus side, these shoes have a very classic, sleek design and while I think the other Jessica Simpson style with the toebox is cute, I'm not a fan of the squared toe look.   As most of the posters wrote, I agree this shoe is about a half size to one size small. If you like your shoes to have some extra wiggle room for your toes, then I'd recommend getting one size bigger since the straps will keep your foot in place. You can try it at Macy's prior to ordering online. There is a bit of toe cleavage, but I don't mind that.ut works better for the shape of my foot. Buyer beware, these shoes are a narrow fit, so if you have wide feet, it will not look flattering at all.Lastly, there is  about an extra quarter inch hidden wedge, so this flat has a heel height of about 3/4" . It's nicely padded and well made.

column6: Clarks Women's Inframe Ease Water Shoe
column14: I did not want to risk not finding this shoe when the first pair wears out!  I have narrow feet, high arches a morton's neuroma, and swelling in one foot due to edema.. The liner that restricts access for some, provides the sides of my feet and my arches the support desired - even if the laces are loosened for swelling. I added regular OTC insoles as I did not like the texture of the rubber insole against my foot.  My first pair has been on several heavy walking tours and hikes during the past 15 months. They provide my feet the support they need while letting them breath.

column14: This is a beautiful hat. Unfortunately, like another purchaser noted about theirs, mine arrived crushed too! What was so odd about it is that the box was intact and pristine. Were it not for the fact that I am familiar with straw hats and was able to manipulate it back into good condition (I had planned to where it out that night) I would have returned it. Any other product or time I would have sent it back. That being said, I will reiterate that this is a nice looking hat. It wears comfortably. In fact, today was a sunny 108. Given the price, these are about as good as I could expect with better construction than I would have expected. I can't say how long they'll actually last but they seem to be fairly durable. Only time can tell how durable they actually are.

A couple of things I think these sandals do really right are related to comfort. The grey portion of the inner sole looks a lot rougher in the picture than it is. It's squishy enough that it actually feels reasonably comfortable. The band comes out of the sides instead of the top of the sole. I've tried some where the band comes out of the top and the result is never pleasant.

There's only a couple things I would change, given the chance. I'd lighten the sole (and make it more flexible in the process) by adding deep groves to it width-wise. I'd also shorten the band so it wouldn't cover my toes but I've yet to see any sandal that does that. Due to the thickness and inflexibility of the sole, it's a little heavier than I'd like and it smacks down rather loudly when I walk down steps. That said, these are very minor problems.

column13: I love Havaianas but straps are too cheap.
column14:
I used a pair of Havaianas for about 6 years and they were extremely comfortable and durable. They were a little different from this one though : the strap was not slim. With this slim strap , the flip-flops are a little bit on the tight side. I thought they might get a little more comfortable after a while but I have been using them for 2 months now and the strap is still too tight and if I wear them for couple of hours or so, they usually leave the strap mark on top of my feet. While I was able to wear my previous Havaianas for more than 2 hours, I cannot do the same with these ones.

That is said, I am using these shoes when in the house as house slippers and/or if and when I got beach/ lakeside. Hence, they do the work. As a brand, I like Havaianas and I think I will get another pair not necessarily this model but with one with a more elastic strap.

EDIT: Strap just broke and not because of overuse. I wear - used to wear- these at home most of the time and suddenly the strap just broke. I still like this brand but I think perhaps this specific model is not as study as other ones.

column14: Recently I had several problems with my feet, including a recurrence of plantar fasciitis in my left foot.  Only time heals that completely (if ever), but these Teva Tirra shoes feel great.  I can walk for quite a long time (I'm 82) without pain, and I can honestly say they are the most comfortable shoes I've had in recent years. I bought the size I normally wear, and they fit well all over, with plenty of adjustable straps.  They're rugged, they're comfortable, have a good arch support, and they look good.  What more could I want?  Well, they're not cheap, but I bought them on sale and feel I got a much better bargain than purchasing cheap shoes that don't fit or don't last.  I highly recommend them.

column6: Frye Womens Jesse Bohemian Sandal
column13: A Cautionary Tale of Shoes and Cigarettes
column14:
I bought these from the Frye website, so full disclosure. I first ordered them in my normal size 7.5 but they were so tight across that I couldn't comfortably get my foot in the shoe. Sent them back and got the 8. Still a little tight but I could get my foot in the shoe. I decided to take a chance and have them stretched. I took them to a shoe repair place around the corner from where I work. When I walked into the shop I noticed that the people working there must smoke like, 2 packs a day! The smell was pretty bad. I ended up leaving the shoes to be stretched. It cost me $10. I picked them up the following week and, in that time, the shoes managed to pick up the smell of cigarette smoke. Damn shoes!! Ok, I guess I should have known better but it truly didn't occur to me that my shoes would smell like they had an unfortunate smoking habit after being in the shop for 5 days. I'm telling you this because I don't want you to make the same mistake. If you walk into a shoe shop and it smells bad, turn around and leave quickly or your shoes will be smelly thru no fault of your own (other than poor judgement).

So how did these shoes fit after being stretched? Well, the shoe guy stretched them too much in one place on the inside by my arch and this caused them to stick out a little. That coupled with the fact that they smelled made me hate them and want to send them back immediately! But I knew that I wouldn't get away with it. So after glaring at them for several days, I placed the shoes in a plastic bag with a few containers of baking soda. After a day or two, I opened the bag- whew! Smelly! But the baking soda did the trick and absorbed the smell. One problem solved, one to go. I tried the shoes on again and realized that they were still the shoes I originally fell in love with even with the over-stretching so I decided to keep them. So glad I did. The problem resolved itself and they have molded to my feet in the best way possible. Now, these are my new favorite shoes (no, really).

Would I recommend these to you? Definately! As long as you have narrow feet or are willing to have them stretched. Just be wary of 'Ole Smoky-The Shoe Repair Guy!

I was on the market for a new set of daily-driver dress shoes for work due to my old pair wearing out. This was my first time buying shoes online so I did not have set expectations.

From reading other Amazon reviews I was able to learn a few key points which made this buying experience successful:
-Formal shoe size is about 1 size less than well-fitting running or tennis shoes.
-These shoes have ample (medium) arch support
-Shoes for medium/narrow feet

At this point it has been weeks and daily-driving these shoes has been great. The glossed look certainly seems to outshow my previous matte wingtips. I appreciate the shoe sole texture now with them on my feet- striped gripping rubber on the heel and smooth front-end. Shoe sizing was a deal-breaker for me, though with regular-sized feet I went with 1 size down from my running shoes and am glad I did.

column6: Scarleton Chain Embossed Accent Tote Bag H1406
column14:
In my search for a new handbag, the Scarleton brand kept popping up. They seemed to offer handbags in a variety of styles at reasonable prices.

When I saw this one, I fell in love. It looked like everything I wanted:

-A practical crossbody bag roomy enough to hold all of my junk

-A simple, classic design

(I'm pretty sure my mom had a bag in the eighties similar to this one.)

-A bag with great reviews

This bag met all criteria, and best of all, the price was right. I placed my order, and two days later, the bag arrived on my doorstep. I was so excited.

That excitement soon turned to disappointment.

I did not have extraordinarily high expectations for this faux leather, no-name bag, but I've bought plenty of satisfactory faux leather, no-name bags at similar prices in the past 20 years. This bag was not a keeper.

The bag was nicely packaged in a plastic Scarleton bag. The bag had an "S" on it in an elaborate font, and it also said Los Angeles. Ooh, fancy! The handles were individually wrapped for protection.

Maybe I'm misunderstanding something, but the bag comes with what appears to be a luggage tag. I've never had a luggage tag on a purse. Maybe it's for a photo? Regardless, mine was slightly different from the one in the photo. That's no big deal. I'm just pointing it out. If you don't want it, it can be easily removed.

At first glance, the bag looked pretty decent. It has two main interior compartments that are separated by a zipper compartment. The interior fabric is brown, which would not have been my first color choice. However, compared to a black interior, the brown interior likely would make it easier for you to find your belongings.

Unfortunately, the bag seemed very cheaply made. The exterior material felt like cheap plastic. You wouldn't be fooling anyone there. I don't see how anyone could ever mistake it for leather. The interior lining was even worse. It had a rough texture and felt--well--cheap.

The bag itself is pretty photogenic, but in reality, it looked like they had cut every possible corner in making it. Maybe one star is harsh, but it's not a bag I would ever describe as nice. If I had seen this bag in a store, I would not have bought it at any price., but in reality, it looked like they had cut every possible corner in making it. Maybe one star is harsh, but it's not a bag I would ever describe as nice. If I had seen this bag in a store, I would not have bought it at any price.

There is no country of origin on the frames or literature, and there is no size designation imprinted either.  The gold frame is shiny and finished well, the plastic part is also finished well and very smooth, and each screw is secured.  The plastic lenses are gray in the pair I have and the protection from the sun is satisfactory for everyday wear.  I would not wear these for sports or perhaps on the water, but as fashion eyeware, they are superb.  Fortunately, I have a case in which to protect these shades because they are packaged simply in a plastic bag.  I received a pair for evaluation and judging from this pair, they are very well made and attractive.

column6: Vionic Alanis Women's Toe-post Wedge Sandal
column14:
I love these shoes! I've been wearing them in the house ever since I got them just to be sure they fit before I wore them outside. Once my feet got adjusted to them, I don't want to wear any other shoe.

The first day I got these I wore them at least 5 hrs. (On carpeting, wood floors & ceramic tile). When I took them off before bed that night, my feet were killing me! The arches of my feet felt like they had a thousand needles sticking them! My feet continued to get that same feeling for another day when j took them off. However that feeling it lessened every day and now I don't have it at all.

I had high arches and I think they've fallen(?) some over time. I believe the pain I experienced was probably from the shoe correcting my foot.

I teach elementary school and plan on wearing these at least 50% of the time. They have a Nice, firm cushion foot bed that really cups your foot.

As for sizing, I would recommend ordering your true size. I usually wear an 8.5 but got these in an 8. (I get a 9 in boots.) My feet are at the ends and barely staying on the sides. I would prefer the next size up but just decided to keep them because I didn't want to deal with the hassle of sending them back.

The print on this shoe is adorable! It has a lot of colors in it, but I donâ€™t think itâ€™s too hard to match. Iâ€™m really happy to have found a cute, comfortable and unique flat - Iâ€™m finding that I want to spend less and less time in heels the older I get. I like the little heart shaped pad on the ball of the foot - this is an improvement over older pairs of Poetic License shoes I have, which didnâ€™t have any padding at all. These did rub a little on the tops of my toe knuckles when they were still breaking in, but that seems to be improving. column6: Scarpa Men's Terra GTX Hiking Boot
column13: UPSIZE!  The SCARPA TERRAs are UNSURPASSED!
column14: SCARPA quality is unsurpassed...by them a size larger!  I tried on boots from LOWA, Merrell, Oboz, Vasque...then settled on Scarpa Terras.  With the exception of Salomon boots run a half size larger), the rest all seem to run a half size to a size smaller than labeled.  The difference with the SCARPAs is that after sizing up from a 44 to a 45, the boots fit as if they were molded to my feet.  Sized up, the arch was in the right spot. Sizing up gives you more room in the toe box, which is slightly pointer at your everyday size.  Now, pull the speed laces...truly a pleasure to cinch up the SCARPAs, quickly and without fuss.  The boot has stood up well to repeated hiking.  It is a responsive boot, providing good trail feel while connecting you to the surface underfoot, without exposing you to rocks and rills as many of the sneaker type designs will.  The Scarpas provide excellent ankle support.  Best of all, you feel as if the boot is a part of your leg rather than a clunky add on; they are surprisingly light and move with you seamlessly.  If you upsize right off the bat, you will love this boot.  Pound for pound, it is the best boot that I have ever owned for trail hiking.

column6: Native Jefferson
column14: I bought these for a 10-day annual river trip in California. The river is very rocky, so it's essential to have water shoes. In past years, I have worn Crocs, but they have their issues, so I wanted to try something new. I first saw these on my 2-year old nephew and when I learned they came in adult sizes, I couldn't wait to try them out. First thing to know is that they look fantastic. Very cute shoe. They are also quite comfortable when just walking around. My feet (which are prone to getting too hot) were not too hot in these. However, they turned out not to be that great on the water. They got a ton-- and I mean a TON-- of rocks in them. I'd shake out the shoes after being on the river for a few hours, and dozens of pebbles would fall out, every time. OUCH. In terms of sizing, I'm an 8.5 and these were only available in 8 or 9, so I went with the 9 based on reviews. They are slightly too big, especially in the length (which might explain some of the pebbles), but I'm pretty sure a size 8 would have been much too tight across the top of my foot. So I'm giving them three stars for just being okay. They look good but could fit better and could definitely do a better job of keeping the rocks out. However, if you're just going to use them at the pool or someplace that is not full of rocks or sand, these will probably be excellent. I do agree with other reviewers and suggest that if you're in between sizes, you go up rather than down. It won't be a perfect fit, probably, but nothing is worse than shoes that are too tight (and these do not stretch out when wet-- the opposite, in fact.)

column6: Mens Slip On Water Pool Aqua Sock
column14:
I bought these for a vacation trip. Used them for about an hour to walk on a rocky beach that was not suitable for bare feet. I thought they felt a bit weird, and when I got out of the water I noticed that the glue between the pad and the inside of the shoe was soft, and the pad was moving all over the inside of the shoe, bunching up. I went to the local beach shop and bought a different pair. No problems.
After these shoes dried, the bottom pad seemed secure again. Doesn't make sense to have a water shoe that gets affected by water, does it?

I would say the shoes look nice, but the pad is going to come apart on you. They need to find a better way of securing the pad in the bottom.

column6: Pursfection EXPANDABLE Purse Organizer
column13: BE CERTAIN OF WHAT YOU ARE ORDERING!
column14: Prior to placing my order, I was toggling back and forth trying to decide on colors since I was purchasing as Christmas presents for my daughters. I realized the prices varied but that happens frequently on Amazon with color selections, so I did not notice the stylings were changing with each toggle. Upon receiving the shipment of the organizers, I realized the black, from LilGift, is different from what is depicted here and does not expand as the brown and bronze from Yagoozon. Rather than expanding horizontally, the black organizer has a fold down fabric which can be extended vertically. If you are looking for a horizontal expandable purse organizer, order a color other than black. As far as the functionality of the organizer, I believe it will help my daughters keep their totes and purses organized but I will have to decide who gets the one that does not expand horizontally. Also, the horizontal expandable organizers were supposed to include purse hangers, but did not.
