column14:
I am a big Poetic Licence fan, and have many pairs but they are mostly heels. Iâ€™ve been trying to get away from wearing heels so much (just not practical for my work environment!) so I was happy to find some cute flats from one of my favorite brands! I loved the colors of these shoes - especially since green and gold are my universtiy colors! There are other colors besides those of course, but itâ€™s a subtle nod to the Bears :) The colors make them a little hard to match with outfits, but if you stick with more solids and arenâ€™t afraid to go bold, there are plenty of things to wear them with!

These shoes are pretty comfortable, and felt that way right out of the box. The strap doesnâ€™t dig in and the heel doesnâ€™t rub. If I walk a long way in these the edge of the toe section does start to rub on the knuckles of my pinky and big toes. It hasnâ€™t caused any blisters yet, but I probably wouldnâ€™t wear these out if I knew I was going to be doing a lot of walking. The rubbing may improve if they break in a little more too. I also appreciate the little heart padded section underneath the ball of the foot. Just makes the shoe a little more comfy. You can probably tell this from the pictures, but there is no arch support in this shoe. Still - I recommend these for a cute and different flat!

I loved the look of these shoes when I saw them on Amazon. The camel color was my favorite. I thought the cork look with the little spots of color was so unique, and I loved the heel height. Unfortunately, I found these shoes to be a little tight and stiff. I can get them on in the morning, but if Iâ€™m on my feet much during the day and my feet swell at all the shoes donâ€™t feel very comfortable. If I could go back and order a size up I would, but they are out of stock. I do like the little heart shaped padding on the ball of the foot, though. And these may get more comfortable if I make an effort to get them broken in. I donâ€™t know if I will take the time for that though.

In the end, Iâ€™m going to keep them because I really do think they are attractive and interesting shoes. I think they are a good neutral shoe, with some fun visual interest. Iâ€™ll try them again when the weather gets cooler, and they are ok for wearing a few hours at a time, but I wonâ€™t be wearing them to work if I know Iâ€™m going to be running errands after - they just arenâ€™t comfortable enough for that.

I love these flip flops. They are a bit dressier than regular flip flops, yet have all the functionality. I wear these for kayaking. yep. You can step into the water, even if the bottom is rocky or muddy, and they stay on. Because the top part hugs the foot higher than normal flip flops these stay on in the water, while your toes are free and comfortable. In the kayak, it's easy to kick them off and then slip then on when you need it. When I'm done kayaking, and we go to lunch or dinner, I don't have to switch shoes. I wash them out in the lake, and they are good to go - function, comfort, and style. How often do you find that in one shoe???
I went to visit my mom in Florida and she appropriated these. Did I mention how soft and comfortable the footbed is? It's like walking on a cloud. So... now I have to buy another pair.

column6: NVIDIA SHIELD Pro (2015)
column14: Definitely not recommended for everyone. Know what you are getting into before you buy. I have an NVidia Shield tablet and so was expecting the same or better out of the NVidia Shield. Instead, even though the Shield has better and more versatile hardware, its software (version 1.3) is drastically reduced (Android TV instead of Android, Plex TV instead of Plex Android, lack of muliple account support, limited search results, etc..) which greatly cuts back on its capabilities. Hopefully in the future they will fix the software and turn it into a great device.  Comparison of NVidia Shield Tablet and the NVidia Shield: NVidia Shield Tablet: 1. Runs Android 2. Casts to TV either via it HDMI connector or ChromeCast 3. Plays all Android games and steams them all to TV. 4. Supports full Plex, Netflix, etc for video streaming. Full search, folders, and full music shuffle in Plex. 5. Has PC game streaming. 6. Supports multiple users accounts through Android OS.  NVidia Shield: 1. Runs Android TV. 2. Cast to TV via HDMI connector. 3. Plays only those few Android games chosen to be playable for TV (even though they really all are). 4. Uses a reduced Plex TV version software that does not provide the functionality of the Android or PC versions of Plex; does not support folders, only shows first 15 in a search so cannot get through a series if it has more than 15 episodes without having to resort to scrolling down through a list of ALL. Plex music section also does not Shuffle the entire list, you must first go into an album or collection of songs and it'll shuffle only those. By comparison Plex for Android lets me Shuffle my entire Music library straight from the root level. Also, voice search does not work in Netflix, will revert to typed input. 5. Has PC game streaming. 6. Does NOT support multiple user accounts (either through the shield, Plex, or PC Games). Be careful, if this is for a family whoever uses their account opens themselves up for everyone. For the software it is safest to log out of everything when done playing or you may find your kid got into your adult movies, or played over your favorite PC game.  Bottom line: If you are single or don't mind other people having access to your account and save games or you just want a simple interface then this is a pretty good device with potential to maybe be an awesome device in the future. But is you are more of a power user and want to "have it all" then you might want to wait and see where they go with this because you are not their target audience.

column6: Nintendo 3DS XL Super Mario Bros 2 Limited Edition
column13: This is a great bundle (provided you like how the case looks) and ...
column14:
This is a great bundle (provided you like how the case looks) and IMO a great deal. I don't buy consoles very often and I consider myself a casual game player; I play on this probably 4-6 hours a week. Maybe more, because it's so easy to pick-up and put down all day exactly where you left off just by closing it.

I owned the very first DS when it came out and I had been thinking for a long time about upgrading. 3d as a feature wasn't a big seller for me but I love how it's used in this. The 3d camera feature is pretty fun even though it's novelty wears off quickly, but the 3d games look AWESOME. Esp. the one that comes with it. And they make it so convenient to toggle the level of 3d and even turn it off super easily based on how far you hold it from your face.

Nintendo so often gets it just right; they get what is fun and appealing and realize how colorful and fun graphics can even top more advanced and detailed graphics the other systems have. Downloading games is convenient and easy. I thought a couple of game downloads would take up all the storage on the thing without an additional memory card but so far still has plenty of room. The battery last a good long time and it charges very quickly. I love taking this with me for times when I'm waiting during the day and I love playing during free times.

This is a great all-around hand console with a nice big screen that I think most people would love. When I first got it I thought it was bulky compared to my original DS but I adjusted quickly and now prefer the bigger screen. My only minor gripe is that the volume slider is right where you hold it on the right and I'm sure will get even looser, so you end up unintentionally increasing the volume while you play.

I'm pretty frugal and this was a big purchase for me someone who isn't a heavy gamer. I have bought many games (I check the reviews and so far I've really liked all of them) and I'm so happy with this purchase.

column6: NES Advantage Joystick
column13: I received this in great condition (much more than the last one I ordered) ...
column14:
I received this in great condition (much more than the last one I ordered) and I found that it functioned just as expected. This joystick allows more functionality than the original NES controller. It allows you to go super fast in Mario Brothers and super slow. I loved this for doing more in Mario Brothers and I even played better than with the original controller. However, you might ask, "Should I buy it?" Honestly, probably not. This is more of a gimmick than something that actually does something useful, and if you find it for a cheaper price, then I would consider it if I were you.

PROS:
-Allows more functionality in games, such as controllable super fast modes and slow modes, multiple A-B button input with just the touch of A or B once.
-Better controllable than other controllers/joysticks

CONS:
-More of a gimmick than something useful

column6: Castlevania: Lords of Shadow 2
column14: â€œLords of Shadow 2,â€ an action game in the vein of â€œDevil May Cry,â€ starts out competently enough during its early moments, giving you hope. But slowly over the course of its dozen + hours did I finally lose all patience with it. There came a point when I simply wanted to run past enemies. Not because I couldnâ€™t defeat them or because I didnâ€™t need any more experience points, but because the combat just becomes a tiring slog. Near the end, enemies take so many hits, use so many unblockable attacks, and countering seems so ineffective and useless so often that whatever fun there was had long since evaporated. And of course thereâ€™s hardly a moment that goes by when playing â€œLoS2â€ that you arenâ€™t bombarded by help tips flashing across the screen, constantly reminding you to spend your experience points, or to check out the artwork youâ€™ve unlocked, or to use one of the many abilities you have to solve the sometimes frustrating environmental puzzles. Sure, you could turn it off in the options. But when you find yourself stuck, youâ€™ll have to keep turning it back on. Only in NG+ when youâ€™ve figured everything out can you rid yourself of this aggravation, which donâ€™t just stay on the screen for a second, but remain there, pulsing, making a little repeating chime sound as if to say, â€œdo what I tell you!â€ Then thereâ€™s the design of the world itself, which is an incoherent mess to navigate through. Instead of being broken up into levels or missions, itâ€™s structured similar to past Metroidvania style games in the series, or tries to be, where various sections of the world are linked together, except this time without a helpful map to guide you. Thereâ€™s no sense of space or location. No way to tell which way is which other than by depending entirely on the waypoint of the mini map. column6: Zombie Army Trilogy
column13: A refreshing online experience despite the exhausted zombie theme
column14:
At first I felt this would be a title I would for sure regret purchasing, but it actually became oddly addicting the more I played. Visually it is pretty unimpressive, but that is to be expected from a game of its age. The audio is solid, though I did find that the sound of lurking zombies to not always be a good guide as to how close they may be, or what direction they may be coming from. Despite that the audio is still where this game shines, providing a cheezy horror flick tone that just fits this game perfectly, setting a mood that keeps this exhausted genre oddly refreshing.

Solo campaign is for sure challenging, which is probably why I found myself enjoying this game a lot more when it was with the company of others. Just seems a lot more manageable that way, and the player revives make a huge difference and take away a lot of the frustration that was experienced when playing alone. It also just feels like a game that is meant to be played with others as communication among teammates was often what made or broke apart a group. Finding a group doesn't take too long but this game is flying under most people's radar so the community really isn't there just yet.

Just wish a few little game modes were included, such as a firing range so you can get a feel for some of the weapons that the game offers. Not having this isn't a deal breaker, but would have been appreciated as the options of campaign mode and horde mode don't leave me feeling fully satisfied in the variety, not for the retail price of $49.99 at least.

Overall, I am happy I picked this game up. The Zombie theme is definitely growing old, but Zombie Army Trilogy is still very enjoyable and a great option if you're looking for a game to play with friends.

column6: Paper Mario: Sticker Star
column13: This game gets so much hate. Granted
column14:
This game gets so much hate. Granted, PM has been a straightforward RPG ever since the beginning. And of course, it is totally reasonable for people to have been deeply disappointed when it did not follow the same formula. It IS a very flawed game, no doubt about it. But I still think people should at least give it a try (especially if it is at a bargain bin price), and here is why:

The Soundtrack

The soundtrack is one of the better parts of this game. I don't think I have ever heard a Mario soundtrack as awesome as this one. Very jazzy, full of life, and I like how they remix old tunes.

No "Experience"

I like how this game handles battle rewards. One main gripe from people who played it is that you get no "experience" and thus each battle is pointless. I beg to differ. You get coins after each battle, coins which you use to buy Thing stickers, which are powerful and fun to watch in battle.

And no, you don't get experience in the traditional sense. In most games, you can simply grind to beat enemies and bosses. Not so here. You get experience by learning the ins and outs of the stickers you have collected. You learn how best to time your button presses for each different sticker (a la Mario and Luigi games), and you learn which stickers work best against each type of enemy. If anything, this game does the concept of "experience" right, whereas other RPGs simply let you get by through the accumulation of points, which make your character hit harder. That's not really experience, if you ask me. It's more like a Zelda game (an action RPG). You do get experience, but not in the form of points you accumulate. Instead, you learn which of your weapons works best against which type of enemy, how long to charge a weapon, and where to hit an enemy.

The Visuals

This is another part that I think was done excellently. Paper Mario was made to be played in 3D. This game is a perfect example of why. Everything just comes to life. You really have to experience it for yourself, IMO.

The Writing

No, you don't really get a good story. However, its obvious that the game had good writers anyway. Most toads say funny things that actually make you chuckle. There are some absolutely brilliant parts, where I am sure the game would have been even better had they made the story an even bigger part of the game. But as it stands, the game has better writing than some of the Mario and Luigi RPGs. Overall, it's very witty and charming. No, none of the toads have names, but they all say the darnest things. And the way in which the writers describe "Things" in this game is brilliant, and full of comedy. You won't be LOLing, but it'll make you smile and giggle.

In terms of writing, I would say it goes like this:

Bowser's Inside Story>Superstar Saga> Sticker Star> Partners In Time> Dream Team

Overall, I say TRY this game. If you don't like it, sell it. But it's worth a try in my opinion. Don't expect an old school Paper Mario and you may come to like it too.

column6: The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt
column13: Coming from a person who doesnt really care for RPGs
column14:
I'm not a big fan of RPG's. In fact i rarely play them. So far the RPG that have made an impression on me are chronologically star wars KOTOR, Jade Empire both on the original xbox and this one right here: The Witcher 3. I was skeptical all through the release. But i took a leap of faith. Boy am i glad i did. In typical RPG fashion yes it's a little slow. You travel distances to get somewhere and talk to people before starting a quest and it can go back and forth several times. But i found that travelling on horseback to get to a far location on the HUGE map is a good way to take the beautiful vistas of the game. So many details have been poured in this game from the wind blowing through the leaves of trees, to the intricate landscape design. Gameplay wise the same level of care has been applied. The character development, the various items and spells you use in a fight, weapons, armor crafting etc... To go into detail would require a lot of time to explain how the many masterfully designed mechanics work and it is best to leave that pleasant surprise to you. Since patch 1.07 mechanics work much more smoothly since launch.
The story is very engaging although the main quest was a little short for my taste. But to make up for it there s a seemingly endless number of secondary quests and witcher contract that allow you to level up in between main quests.
This is truly a next gen Game and i hope future games, RPG or not take the same level of care to polish their games as this one is.

column6: Just Dance 4
column14: I have been dancing to the Just Dance Wii games for just about a year now. Last June I decided to finally get in shape and lose some weight. Knowing how much I detest exercising I knew I needed to find something that I could stick with in order to achieve my goal of losing 40 pounds. I grew up in the 80s and was a video gamer through and through so when I saw there was a video game that included dancing and music, I had to try it. Just Dance 4 was the first one that I purchased. It was really great so after that I purchased Just Dance Greatest Hits, 2014, and 2015. In my opinion they are all great, some better than others. The songs are also great. You get a real mixture of genres so most everyone can find songs they enjoy dancing to. I just wish Nintendo would release more DLCs and more frequently. I was able to lose those forty pounds by last October and almost a year later have managed to keep it off and maintain using Just Dance and a balanced diet. I am so thankful for these games because if it hadn't been for them, this gamer would probably still be forty pounds heavier and vegging out in front of a different kind of video game. Thank you UBI Soft and Nintendo. I am including an after picture and a picture of all the clothes that I donated because they didn't fit anymore. Thanks to Just Dance and following a balanced diet (logging everything into the Lose it! app daily) I was able to lose the weight.  If you find my review helpful please let me know and if you have any questions or comments, feel free to post them below and I will answer them as quickly as possible.   Thank you for checking out my review.   :)

column6: Tomee Wii U System Controller Carrying Bag M06015
column13: I've got a bit of baggage...
column14:
There's many good things about this bag, and a few things that could be done much better. First off, let me say that it is not made explicitly for the Wii U. The Wii U and Gamepad are held in by velcro straps, meaning that they can be reasonably secure. Despite not being made for the Wii U, it makes up for it by having an incredible amount of storage space and plenty of different pouches for different applications. There's two pouches on the front, two pouches on the inside, and three slots for "disks". Realistically, if you have very thin cases you can fit two or so games in there. Otherwise, I don't suggest using them. It also includes a shoulder strap, but I haven't used it much yet. When you get to it, it fits a ton of things, and one of them is a Wii U. If you need a case, this is probably your best bet.

Pros:
-You can fit a ton of different things in here.
-The gamepad and Wii U remain very secure despite not having specific slots.
-The case itself is pretty light, and the weight will depend entirely on what you put in there.

Cons:
-It's still not made explicitly for the Wii U.
-It looks pretty boring.
-The small game slots are not at all good for games.

List of things I was able to fit in the case all at once:
-Wii U Console
-Wii U Gamepad in soft foam case
-Wii U Pro Controller
-Wii Controller with Nunchuk Attachment
-Gamecube Controller
-Wii U AC Adaptor
-Wii U Gamepad Charger
-Wii/Wii U Sensor Bar
-6 foot HDMI cable
-Wii U Gamecube Adaptor
-2.5" Hard Drive Enclosure
-2 games in small cases
-2 games in full DVD cases

- accomplishment is real. The system of this game is intuitive, optimizing your use of it to have your characters triumph over enemies is intellectual rewarding.
pro - dynamic strategic turn-based combat
- Fighting a single boss from fighting enemies outnumbering oneselves twenty - to - five, and the continuous and surprising scaling between these extremes are as different as playing two separate games. The development of conditional strategies has far more depth than the "mute or hamstring," single button interchanges that more basic rpgs offer (again, wow is alluded to.)
pro - customization
- Diablo 2 style character building. You may have two characters, or four, or in the well-implemented co-op, only one. This hinges upon using lone-wolf or not, a feat (think DnD, any edition) that can channel a balanced but complete amount of ability/attribution/stats that is by default spread across two characters into a single character. The development planning may be either serious or casual, depending on how you like your gaming. Challenging on standard difficulty.
pro - the feeling that any time not spent developing/optimizing characters may be spent developing/optimizing strategy instead, leading to, ultimately, similar feelings of gleeful, smart glory.
pro - modular/randomly generated loot. This is what it's all about, homies.

column6: Dragon Age: Origins
column14:
So I am going through my backlog of 360 games. Finally got around to playing this. I won't do my normal review. I am going to just squeeze in my thoughts about this game overall.

The story is pretty deep and I like how there are factions that you come across. You play as 3 different characters starting from very humble beginnings to actually being a prince. I know I can write some spoilers as this game is old but I prefer to leave some things out in case people haven't played it yet. From that point on, whoever you choose, you start in different places on the map. This game really follows a Dungeons and Dragon approach to its style. There really isn't any exploration as it is not open world. It is more linear than anything else that allows you to see what is around you in a corridor. The way it leads up to the end is okay but there are some boss battles that you need to be well informed about before you battle them. But the way that Bioware brings the 3 kinds of races together is unique. I will say that even if you can figure out some of the story before the end, there are at least 3 big surprises that you don't see coming. And with them giving you the ability to make the choice in the first place, you will be engaged.

For the combat of the game, I found it to be ultimately disappointing. I see why in the Dragon Age 2 they went with the action approach. This game, at least on console, gives you the impression that it is an action RPG when it plays similar to a real time combat RPG along the lines of Final Fantasy 13 but not as fast. Actually it was very similar to Knights of the Old Republic on the Original Xbox where you enter commands and it does what it's suppose to without you necessarily have to push a button. If you can take that, then you will get through the game.

Overall, the game is playable but it wasn't my type of game. So if you are looking at my review, just know that it is not to be compared with modern games. This game came out in 2007 so its more than 7 years old. Graphically it's better looking than it's ps3 counterpart, but it looks horrendous. That is something that usually doesn't bother me but it will bother someone else according to today's standard of even good graphics. Play it to experience it but go in with the expectation that it might feel really archaic.

column6: The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt
column14: I have been a big fan of both previous Witcher games, and I have to admit, I was a bit skeptical going in, mainly because of the big "open world" craze that overtaking the game industry these days. I personally loved the flow, and narrative of the previous games, and hoped that they weren't making an open world game purely for that sake of the large map, and the "go anywhere, do anything" angle purely because it is quickly becoming viewed as a necessity for a successful game these days. But after playing for roughly 40 hours or so, I can safely say that CD Projekt Red did a fantastic job keeping the game focused, but open, not simply because they just could do it, but because it genuinely works well with the progression of both main, and supporting characters. More often than not, I find myself playing through main story quests until I feel like there is something of value to be gained elsewhere. It could be more experience, equipment or gold, or even just revelations on supporting characters, or world lore, but this game managed to find the perfect balance between keeping a focused, story-driven adventure RPG, and an open world, free-form exploration action RPG. It never hurts to be skeptical, but its always nice to be proven wrong for a pleasant surprise. I have yet to see where the story will lead, but so far it has hooked me in completely, and I have no doubt it will end up being a great addition to the series.

column6: GLOW in DARK Playstation 3 PS3 Wireless Game Controller Anti-Slip Silicone Case Skin Protector Cover (Many Colors Available)
column14: A very good skin with a decent amount of glow to the material. Affords a decent grip without being tacky, and doesn't have a bunch of grooves in it to pick up grime. Wiping it clean is easy. It fits my Japanese PS1 dualshock perfectly and adds a lot of size and bulk to the controller, which I like. It may look like a novelty or 'toy' sort of thing, but picking up a controller with one of these on it really lends the feel of picking up 'a piece of gaming equipment' instead of a bit of plastic. When you hold it in your hands, you won't want to chuck the controller down after playing, because you'll worry about it breaking something.   Do put the skin on carefully - it's easy to force the sticks while getting the skin into place over them.  I recommend this skin!  EDIT 11/13/16: I've been using this thing for years now and it still doesn't show any signs of wear. It adds so much comfort to the controller that a normal skinless controller feels strange to my hands now.

column6: Trenro Dual PlayStation/PlayStation 2 to PC USB Controller Adapter
column14: Best controller->USB adapter I've used of any kind. It's why I play PC games, even emulators of other systems, all with my old PS1 Dualshock. Had and used this about 2 years without issue, and had one before that that lasted even longer before it got lost in a move. It's plug-and-play, does not introduce any significant input lag, and has worked with every PS1/PS2 controller I've plugged into it. This device and a Japanese Dualshock 1 are all you need to play most games on most emulated platforms, although you might have to remap controls for some of them. Analog movement works a treat. Ape Escape, a game known for its dependence on dual-stick use, and R4, a racer in which steering with the stick takes an expert's grace, are both perfectly playable using one of these. Of the games I play which have native gamepad support, most allow remapping. When they don't, you can use JoyToKey or similar to remap the buttons to keys and still play. As for emulating DirectInput with a setup like this, it's not worth the trouble IMO and you're better off with another device. But for everything else, this is as simple/inexpensive as 'good and functional' gets.

column6: Sonic Unleashed
column14:
So I have a Wii still and decided to buy this for my 9 year old daughter thinking it would be nice for her. I have to say that I rarely like leaving negative reviews for decent games but this was not a good game. First the story.

Story
I can't really say too many things about the story for the game because it wasn't that great. And don't get me wrong, Mario games aren't much better, but at least you get the gist of it. A princess in dire need for help and a plumber coming to the rescue. It doesn't have to really be like real life but at least something to get you through the game would be good. But in this game, you have the power of a beast in you for some reason and you end up in a town trying to figure out how to leave. You need to find rings in the world to help give you power ups for your beast form. You transform based on the moon if you travel at night. During your regular form you have to talk to villagers to get their problems solved which will help you to taking on missions in the world. The bad part is that most of the times you don't quite get who you should be talking to about missions and then you have drawn out conversations only to realize you are not talking to the right person. They don't do a good job of directing you either so many times you might just end up wandering around without a clue. The story is horrible for a Sonic game and now I see why people don't play Sonic games.

Controls
They are completely wonky. Once you are in a mission, they are standard. I played with the classic remote because trying to use the Wiimote on this thing will make you want to break the tv. I don't know why they did that but the controls are extremely loose for the game meaning that you will find yourself looking like you are flying a spaceship using the Wiimote with the joystick connected. Upon using the classic remote, Sonics standard moves are the power ball (where he revs up into a little blue ball and bursts away), and jumping.Playing in the beast mode you have 2 attacks but it really doesn't matter because both attacks yield the same results.

Overall
I can't even bring myself to keep talking about this game. Sega once stood for something. You see the inspiration in many of their old games. But this was a dud. I played Alpha Protocol which was extremely glitchy, but had an amazing story and only got better once you leveled your character up. This game was uninspired. It's like they churned this out knowing that people would purchase it on Sonics name. I hope future games will at least go in a different direction.

column6: Assassin's Creed Unity
column14:
I played this months after the release-day bugs were fixed, so this review has absolutely nothing to do with any of that nonsense. And I have to say, Assassin's Creed: Unity is a great game... if you're into half of your missions being "chase the man/woman around the streets of Paris." Which, incidentally, is again hampered by the fact that the run button and the climb button are the same button, so if you get too close to a building, wall, or other object, you'll abandon said chase in order to start climbing. Fun! And, hey, if you're into a game series where its 8th major-release removes features that make you stealthy (like whistling while in hiding to attract enemies for the kill, or the ability to dispose of dead bodies) to make way for more poorly executed street brawling, then this is the game for you! Because, clearly, to the developers of this game, "stealth" means "fight in plain sight." Want to fire a stealthy wrist-mounted arrow from the cover of a crowd and still be seen by enemies behind a wall with no direct line-of-sight? AC: Unity has that feature!!! Want to be hit by an enemy's sword because half of the time you don't get the on-screen prompt that he's attacking? Then you should buy this game! Want the most forgettable Romeo-&-Juliet-lite story starring two of the most unlikeable characters in an Assassin's Creed game yet? THEN THIS IS YOUR GAME, MAN! Want to skip the enhanced-for-this-entry grind of collecting in-game money to buy and upgrade your weapons, armor, and stealth tactics by spending actual, real-world cash on microtransactions (beyond the 60 bucks you already spent) to jump to the head of the class because getting there naturally has coincidentally become more tedious than ever before? THEN OH MY GOODNESS YOU NEED TO OWN THIS GAME, LIKE, YESTERDAY!!!

Two stars because the only people not asleep at the wheel at Ubisoft for this vapid disaster are the ones who meticulously rendered late 18th-century Paris into a gorgeous, sprawling virtual landscape. Kudos to those guys and gals. Everyone else should be ashamed of themselves.ris into a gorgeous, sprawling virtual landscape. Kudos to those guys and gals. Everyone else should be ashamed of themselves.

column6: PlayStation 3 500 GB System
column14: Well I had the Slim model which is/was the best PS3 ever made. They all ran pretty hot, and this little bugger is no exception. That's the main problem and concern people have. Sure it will take it's share of abuse, but I doubt nearly as good as the bigger system(s), That's the whole point. This is small, and convenient. I mainly got it for a few "old" games and DNLA content, mp4, avi etc. since I won't buy a PS4 till next year when the price drops and UC4 comes out. Same with the 360, though I'll probably never buy an Xbox One. This is still a great multimedia device, and with all the Samsung, LG, Phillips, and even Sony Streaming/DVD/Bluray devices on the market. It's just silly to pay that much for one of those when you can get this. With the 500gb of space, which you can actually use. Either for games, music, movies etc. Straight off of a flash drive. And never heave to plug anything in, because of the excellent streaming capabilities.  I hooked mine up, and right away the Playstation Store installation crashed the system. So I sighed for a moment and said well, I've seen them all do this, so no biggie. Also I got mine at Wal-Mart, so if i have to return it, no big deal. I use the 360 also for some multimedia stuff, but not much. Mostly old games. The top blu ray door doesn't bother me since my entertainment center is like a desk. Nothing closed in. And I rarely watch discs anyway. But nice to have just in case. I also like the fact that unlike the Roku, you can take this to someones house, have it loaded up with movies etc. and NOT have to have any type of internet connection to watch them. DLNA content of course. So it's very portable. Also being an older system, with all the new UI on it. It's pretty laggy, mostly on the PSN store. The home screen works pretty fluidly. So it's good for a 9 year old device, but that HEAT, with it's small size is my main concern. Though there is a lot of power (for it's time) under the hood for something this small. SoI'll use it, and see if it maintains itself well. Also PS4/Xbone just don't have enough content to justify a purchase at this time. Maybe 2016, Holiday season. We'll see. :)

column6: F1 2015 - Parent
column13: Worth it for the hardcore fan or newcomer to F1 on next gen.
column14:
It would be a 5 star game but they took away features like career mode for example. Here are my pros and cons

Pros:
1-Code masters new handling and physics engine is the closest thing they have had to a simulation type experience. It's not like a full blown sim like on PC but I enjoy the driving and got comfortable with the new engine after 4 full race weekends(hardcore racing gamer)
2- visuals are better than ever but I'm sure that in the future they will get better.
3- 2 seasons in one game is great for anyone smart enough to avoid 2014 as you get the 2014 and 2015 seasons in this game.
4- 1080p and 60 fps gameplay is a plus. It's much more enjoyable imo
5- smartest and most aggressive AI any codemasters game has ever seen. Be ready for quite a challenge on expert difficulty with no assist. It is an amazing experience. Drivers will attack you, make mistakes and defend their positions in a way that will intimidate you yet giving you a challenge at the same time.

Cons:

1- lack of features such as career mode, season challenge, classic cars(but Codies have plan to bringing that back for the 2016 game as well as the other features that we all loved about previous entries)
2- bugs can affect your experience, such as random driver names appearing on screen, crashing, etc but I have only experienced the random names popping up glitch.

In conclusion, if you're a hardcore fan or a new fan to the sport and have a PC, ps4, or a Xbox 1 then you should consider the game. The driving for me is what made it worth it for me.

column6: Myst IV: Revelation
column14:
I am so happy I found a good used copy of this game. I could not find this title or Exile for purchase digitally anywhere. I had to look for a physical copy. I bought the limited edition version which includes Revelations on 2 DVDs and Myst 3 Exile on one DVD, so it was a 3 DVD disc set. The box came in great condition, had everything inside it. The discs were in like new condition. The games installed fine on my Windows 7 64-bit PC, with no issues. Just put DVD in the drive and I selected full install option, Revelation took 8 GB of hard drive space, Exile a little over 2.

A lot of users said you can't run these on Windows 7 64-bit, but I can say, both games play fine on my machine. You might need to change compatibility settings but they do run. My only complaint is Exile runs a little slow, every time you click, instead of instantly going there, the audio repeats or lags a bit, but other than that, that's it.

Exile and Revelations are great games, amazing soundtracks, great story, and the visuals are fantastic. Revelations is more animated and life-like than Exile, but both are great in there own regard. I am so glad I found this great collection to finish off my Myst Series.

column6: Maxrace F.1 converter.3.0
column13: Functional but disappointed with \Force Feedback\" claim"
column14:
First and foremost, yes, you need this to run the most venerable wheel on the market, the Logitech G27. With some minor mapping issues out of the way with the help of the poorly translated user guide, you will be enjoying yourself on the XBox360 with the best wheel on the market. Not the Microsoft has given any competitor to even come close.
If this is your first wheel, great, enjoy. Stop reading. However, if you came from using the first Microsoft Wireless Racing Wheel or have played the G27 on the Playstation you know what Force Feedback is supposed to be and using this won't give you that. Force Feedback gives you a continually varying amount of input, depending on what is napping with the car.
Imagine your approaching a decreasing radius turn at speed. You begin to turn the wheel but obviously can't feel the amount of G-forces that are happening. Force Feedback supplies that input by gradually increasing the force it takes to continue turning the wheel as the G-forces increase. Where this is especially important is when suddenly the wheel goes "light" or easy to turn. This means you've lost traction and you're headed for an important meeting with the outside wall. Newton, you fickle bitch. Having correct Force Feedback helps you run that ragged edge and makes the world on enjoying the simulated experience.
With the Maxrace Converter, your G27 thinks it's a handheld controller and the steering wheel is a thumb stick. It will provide even pressure that wants to self-center the wheel no matter what is happening in the game or how much you are turning the wheel. When you hit something or do anything where the handheld controller would vibrate, the wheel will wiggle back four or five times.
Bottom line is for what this module costs, you could get a good used Playstation 3 and a copy of Grand Turismo and skip the module entirely.

column6: XenoBlade Chronicles
column13: I didn't get it at first but now I do
column14:
I didn't get it at first why this game was such a cult Wii game but now I do.
It takes a little time diving into it, and I strongly suggest that you understand how all your characters could work together.
I played about half the game just giving each character what I felt was their best skills, but not thinking of a team skillset... once I did that the game was so much easier, or my party was so much more effective.
I don't agree with many reviews online saying that you need to use this party or this character for this or that... I just played with the characters I liked and it all worked out for me. (There is some major benefits of using magic users against higher level monsters, but apart from that it doesn't really matter).

It took me about 100 hours to finish the game, with a lot of the side quests, but not all of them.
100 hours for a game is really good, especially in one such as this where you get to really appreciate some of your characters.

I removed one star for the end game part.
I tried my best to get most of the quests I cared for done before the ending (mostly the extra skill trees and swords related quests), but that got me to be way too strong against the last boss... it was not even fun. (I was around level 84).
And once I defeated the game, I could not go back to venture the world to finish the other quests... I would have to either use an earlier save, or go through a New Game Plus, which could be ok if I didn't have to redo some of the longest quests (like Colony 6 reconstruction...).

column6: Fortune Street
column13: Addicting spin on Monopoly.  Much more challenging and interesting.
column14:
There are two modes in this Monopoly-esque game: an easy mode that plays like Monopoly and is easy for all ages and a standard mode that allows players to buy and sell stocks, complicating their abilities to earn $$ and dominate other players. Quite honestly, I learned a little about how stocks work playing this game! The whole family enjoys this game but be forewarned: if Monopoly is one of those games that can get you really cranky if you're losing or turn you into a greedy megalomaniac if you're winning then use caution with whom you play! (You can play solo, and there are tons of little things to unlock and collect. It can be quite challenging.)

The game uses a variety of characters from the Mario and DragonQuest games, or you can use your own Miis. When you play solo there's a lot of dialogue from the characters and it really slows your game down. Fortunately there are options to turn off the dialogue and to adjust the game's speed. But the coolest features of this game are the variety of playing boards that are used. Each have their own strengths and strategies. All of the unlockable boards are worth unlocking (and this will take some time spent with the game doing so in a one player mode) especially the final board for the easy play games. Finish 1st through 3rd (out of four players--the computer will fill in for any non-human player and you always have to play with four) and earn points to unlock different character movements and costumes (and there are a lot--I fell short of opening all but about 7).

Games take about an hour to two to complete and there is a save feature so you can come back to a game that you're doing great on if you don't have time to finish it in one sitting. Our family will be keeping this game as long as we keep our Wii.

column6: Replacement Swap thumbsticks Fits for PS4 DualShock 4 & Xbox one Controller
column14:
Fantastic replacement for the existing sticks. With a brief bit of a tutorial on Youtube I was able to easily take apart the controller and install them. As a gaming enthusiast the stock plastic sticks' rubber grip had worn down to being smooth and kind of spongy, but I highly doubt that it'll be so easy to wear down aluminum. They fit great (you might have to press a bit, don't be afraid of using a little elbow, the controllers are more solidly built than they appear) and after a couple hours on the Witcher I've gotten used to the slightly different stick face. A brilliant upgrade- if I get a second controller, I'm getting a second set. If my first controller breaks, I'm harvesting the first pair to use in the replacement.

The D-Pad is not metal, but plastic, and so I didn't fit it on my controller, but I'm certainly keeping it around. Never hurts to have a spare.

column6: Nyko Charge Base
column13: Crippled after only a few months.
column14:
Crippled after a few months. I bought this for my son and after a few months, one of the ports on the base (the one closest to the charging display) does not appear to charge. Placing the controller on the port behaves normally at first. After a few seconds, the red LED goes out and the controller icon just flashes.
Bad battery? No. you can place that same controller on the other port and it will continue to charge like normal. If we place his second controller on the same port, the same thing happens again. Place the second controller on the other port, it charges fine. The issue follows the port on the base.
I have emailed Nyko, no response yet. I have searched the web for this issue, nothing. I have tried to see if I could download the manual, nothing. I found the original manual and it has nothing for troubleshooting other than to call a number during business hours (when I work) or their web address, which is where I left the email.
This is not looking good. So although we can charge, we can only charge one station at a time.

I will try and update this when I get a resolution or if I get any response from Nyko.

column6: 8bitdo SNES30 Wireless Bluetooth Controller Dual Classic Joystick for IOS / Android Gamepad - PC Mac Linux
column14:
I love the SNES controller. I thought this would be the perfect thing to use to play emulators with between my phone, laptop, and desktop computers. For the first 2 hours I had the controller, I was so happy I found this thing. The build quality is fantastic and it pairs to all my devices in seconds!

Then I waited a couple hours and tried pairing the controller again. All of a sudden it just doesn't want to work correctly. All my devices recognize it, and it does pair, but then it just doesn't work. My computer/phone will say that it's paired but the LED won't stay lit indicating that it is paired. I tried holding select to clear the pairing info, I tried every mode, clearing the pairing info between each try. I tried updating to the latest firmware. Nothing worked. The only way I can use this with bluetooth is to reset it to factory settings every time and even then it only works for a few hours. If you set the thing down for 10 minutes it goes into sleep mode, and during this time whatever happens to make the bluetooth not work anymore happens. So basically every time you want to use it you have to reset it completely.

It works fine when you plug it in but it still goes into sleep mode, which makes no sense. If it's receiving power over USB then why on earth does it have to go to sleep after 10 minutes of no use.

It's nothing but trouble, but when it works it's awesome. I hate it.

column6: Final Fantasy XIV: A Realm Reborn 60 Day Time Card
column13: There is a limit of how many of these cards you can stack. And this is a safer way to pay for your subscription.
column14:
Be sure to order this with 2 weeks out from your time running out in case there is a problem with the shipping of this time card. Although I had problems with my Order coming out of Oakland California, this product is best if you buy the ONLINE CODE because you get it right away. However if you can only pay by a check this is your only option. Now bear in mind this is a time card not a bonus code or Collector edition code. This product does as it advertises and gives you 60 days. Plus be careful if you are going to stack these codes you can only prepay for 6 months (180 days) so if you buy 3 of these and you have time left use 1 of the codes and look at the days left if you have less than 120 or less days then you can add the 3rd one. But the max is 180 days do not put the 3rd code on until you are 120 days or less out from the end of the prepaid time.

In addition, you now get veteran rewards by the total days subscribed not time played. So if you are a new player and you add 2 cards you will get the rewards for those days Ranks 1 2 and 3 for the first 120 days the next card you put on will give you the 180 days (Rank 4) rewards the 270 day reward (rank 5) rewards will come on after the next 2 cards are added When I add this code I will be 30 days shy of rank 5 and I cannot add another code for a bit because I will have around 127 days left so I have to wait until I am 120 or less to add the next code.

This is the SAFEST way to play because with all the websites being hacked having your credit card information on your account isn't safe with the fact that places like SONY has proven that. And this is also a good way to give a gift code to a friend/family member who plays.

I think the song selection is great, and there really is something for everyone. The dances are fun and there seems to be something for every level of dancer. I play mostly by myself, but occasionally my husband will play. I admit heâ€™s not a big fan because he feels like he isnâ€™t good at it. I feel like the menus are a little tedious to scroll through, but itâ€™s not too bad. Iâ€™m also not a big fan of the sweat mode - Iâ€™d like to have an exercise mode that goes directly from one song to the next without me having to push any buttons. However, I donâ€™t know if this game doesnâ€™t have it or I just havenâ€™t figured out how to make it work. Honestly I havenâ€™t spent much time trying to figure it out since I have other exercise games that work exactly how I want without my having to think too hard :)

column6: Hori (Ps4/ps3 Correspondence) Real Arcade Controller Pro.V Silent [PlayStation 4]
column13: Great stick so far no complaints
column14:
Great stick so far no complaints. The Hayabusa stick is a little more loose than the Sanwa sticks in most sticks. On the other hand the Kuro buttons take a little more pressure than a Sanwa OBSF. If you have used a madcatz TE stick they use Sanwa parts. The parts overall are much much more quiet than non silent buttons. I am able to play in a 3 bedroom apartment at 3am without waking anyone up!

The chassis is made of hard sturdy plastic which ends up making the stick quite light. I could see some people who play with their stick vigorously have slipping issues although i have had none. The stick worked right out of the box with my pc and Windows 10. The most important decision would be if you like a looser stick. If possible play on a fightstick with a Sanwa installed and try to imagine it a little bit looser. Overall i am very happy with my purchase.

column6: Farming Simulator
column13: Fun Driving Around & Working With Realistic Machines!
column14:
My 8 year old loves this game! He has always been fascinated with farming equipment and this game has brought them to life for him. Now since he is young he doesn't play the game to its fullest with the the missions or real farm building. My son loves to maneuver the trucks and other equipment around and is slowly figuring out more and more of the game. There is some reading required about how to work machines and so forth that he needs help with but he loves it. The animation is amazing and very realistic. The game actually uses a new visual technology called PBR, or physically-based rendering. The technology helps to produce a photorealistic rendering by simulating how the light behaves on materials like metal, plastic, glass and more.

A new activity that is in this game is Woodcutting. This is my son's favorite activity. Every time I catch him playing the game he is woodcutting. There are numerous vehicles and machines to woodcut including tree cutters, chainsaws, chippers, trailers and tools for harvesting. Players can sell the wood them cut or process them at the sawmill. Yes you do earn money in the game and that is how you buy more machines and such. There are various jobs on the farm that need to be done and players need to figure out which machines will get the job done and how to use them efficiently.

This game really has so much packed into it to play and explore. My son loves maneuvering the different machines and seeing how they work. It is teaching him problem solving, decision making and budgeting money. He has learned that he doesn't have an endless supply of money so he has learned to earn money and spend it wisely.

So with Farming Simulator 2015 you can now play online with friends in multiplayer mode. We haven't tried this yet but its great that its included for those that do like the online option.

Overall though, Farming Simulator 2015 has become a family favorite between my sons and husband. My boys even like just watching my husband play with the different machines while they cheer him on.even like just watching my husband play with the different machines while they cheer him on.

column6: Cabelas Survival: Shadows of Katmai
column14: I saw the word *Cabelas* and thought to myself "I am certain that they must posses an understanding of *HUNTING*." I saw the word *SURVIVAL* and figured that Cabelas having somewhat an understanding of Hunting should also have a sound grasp on the Alaskan wilderness. Boy was I surprised as it turns out to ASS'U'ME really does make an ASS out of YOU and ME. When I read on the cover "Hunger is a constant threat!" I thought to myself "I suppose that I must eat food in the game to play." What a joke... What it really means is that the second the plane hits the ground about 45 Ravenous wolves attack you mercilessly  Jumping from the wreckage of the plane as if they were cargo, but thats not all. Aside from the Bears being so "HUNGRY" that they decided to start "Hunting" in obscenely large wolf packs with mountain lions, the ASS over head drops of the Moose/Caribu/Goat in their fixed galleries were absolutely pathetic. When I paid money for an artificial existence called "SURVIVAL" I was not expecting to determine how much inexpendable ammunition I could dump across an Alaskan range the resembles the "Prince of Persia the Two Thrones" with a different skin from X-Box original just not put together quiet as well. Although the game is an excellent depiction of Activision's understanding of "SURVIVAL" in any form, I did not enjoy their ignorance to detail.  -Zane Russell Aston

column6: AmazonBasics Heavy-Duty Vault Case for PlayStation Vita and Vita Slim
column13: this case did great, except it can not withstand being ran over ...
column14:
Well, this case did great, except it can not withstand being ran over by a semi truck at 75MPH. Unfortunately, I did something very stupid, and left my Vita on the top of my car in this case. The case did it's job, and actually stayed on the roof of my car until I got to the freeway - that's when I saw the case in my rear view mirror, go flying off the roof. The case actually stayed closed, and I'm guessing the Vita was okay at this point. That's when the semi truck ran it over... I had already began pulling over to the side of the road and backing up, but the pieces I found were barely a Vita anymore. I was able to find both the back and front of the case, the screen of the Vita, most of its components, and the memory card.
There was a nice tire mark on the Vita's screen, which kind of felt like salt on the wound.

I do recommend this case for the original Vita's though, it does great.

column6: Tomb Raider Trilogy
column14:
If you're a fan of the tomb raider series, this one's for you. But if you're like me, and have only played the very first Tomb Raider game (or none at all), then it might take you awhile to get into. Overall, this is a great collection of great games. The only negative thing I have to say about it, is that it is extremely challenging. What I mean is, the games are basically one giant (complex) puzzle. There are no indicators or directions of any kind on what to do--you have to figure everything out yourself. Don't get me wrong, I don't mind challenging games--to an extent. There were times when I became frustrated due to the fact that I didn't know what the heck I was supposed to do. It's all trial and error. On the other hand, that is also what makes this game unique (and why I kept playing it).
So bottom line, you want to something that's going to rack your brain, or if you just want to take a trip down memory lane, then play these games. Just be prepared for some rough times ahead.

column6: Batman: Arkham Knight
column14:
I've read some of the other reviews about this game, and for the most part, they are very well stated and true. So to me, it would be kind of redundant if I reiterate what was already said. Instead, what I'll do is talk about the Batmobile. And the reason for that is because everything else in the game is very similar to the previous titles (aside from the outstanding graphics), which is not a bad thing, as said in another review.

Obviously, the Batmobile is the main attraction of this game, considering it wasn't in the previous installments. That being said, is the Batmobile essential? Was it really necessary for Rocksteady to include this behemoth of a vehicle? Would the game have still been enjoyable without it? These are the questions I pondered as I began my "final" journey as the Batman. And to be honest, it's kind of a love/hate relationship. There were times when I enjoyed racing through the muddy streets of Gotham, or blowing up cars in a thrilling car chase. And then...there were the other times. When the game forced me to maneuver the Batmobile on a very awkward platform, or the tedious tank battles that became more annoying than enjoyable. But hey, these are my opinions. I know other people absolutely love the Batmobile, and that's perfectly fine. I still believe that despite it, it is much faster traversing through Gotham the old fashion way--gliding. And I do enjoy being shot out of the Batmobile like a rocket.

Overall, the Batmobile is cool and all, but isn't necessary, until the game forces you to use it.

column6: The Evil Within
column14:
While I rarely feel strongly enough about a game or item to review it...this was one of those games. Coupled with an unimaginative and plot-less story, you never gain any attachment to the characters in the game outside of the frustration of running up 1 flight of stairs and then huffing and puffing till death. The games atmosphere is by far the best thing about it. The gritty, dark and blood soaked world really does look amazing. But thats where the praise stops. It does a good job of making you want to play through the game for the sheer reason of not wanting to feel like you wasted your money. And thats how I spend my entire 16 begrudging hours in this campaign. The feelings of dissatisfaction being all the way back in chapter 3 with your first boss encounter. Filling the chainsaw toting lunatic with 8 explosive bolts and 4 shotgun rounds to the face and watching him still chase you all over the map knowing full well you have no more ammunition to fight with turns this game of cat and mouse into an hour long circle using the various traps to finish him off. It never really gets any better with the sheer assault of bosses from that point on. This game very quickly departs from a survival game in the sense of wits and becomes a survival game of "run away because we're throwing another boss you need 30 rounds to kill and we've only given you 12". Over and over this repeats itself. If you must play it...I suggest stopping after each of its 15 chapters. This was NOT a return to the horror survival genre with its artificial difficulty and lack of any real scares. The only thing I ever feared in this game was repeating any of the long boring boss fights.

For the record I REALLY wanted to love this game. Maybe that want is what forced me to complete it. But if it wasnt, and the want to feel like I didnt waste my money on it was my primary goal...I failed in that. I still feel like I wasted my money and my time with this game. At this point I feel thisgame has caused me to give up on Survival Horror games. They just simply arent any good anymore.

column6: SmaAcc Vertical Stand with Cooling Fans for PlayStation 4 Console â€“ Dual Charger Station for DS4 DualShock 4 Wireless Controller - Unique Super Silence Design For Free from Noise
column13: Looks and works great. Make sure to turn off fan when not in use.
column14:
When I ordered this, I was concerned it wouldn't fit on our shelf which is 12" tall. Our PS4 was stored horizontally prior. This fit! It's about 11.25" tall with the PS4 on it, but I'd recommend a 12" space.

I love that there's a fan to keep it cool. If you put the USB connection in the front, that allows you to plug it into the front USB port. Our PS4 doesn't have any spare USB ports on the back.

There's a switch to turn off the fan... You will want to do this if you leave PS4 in standby mode, otherwise it will keep running and drawing energy. I don't believe it will turn off on its own once PS4 is cool- that would be a nice feature to have.

The controllers plug in on each side... I love having a spot for the controllers so they will always be charged. The controllers plug in via the port on the bottom of them so if you have a battery back hooked on there like I did, it won't fit. That said, I may not need the battery pack if we put back the controllers every time. Hooking the controllers in takes some focus at first... It's hard to get them just right (particularly as the space is tight on my shelf). They go in at a weird angle. My son (3.5 years old) cannot put them back correctly by himself.

Overall I'm very happy with this product and it looks sharp.
